# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-fifth-avenue
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The **1980 Winter Olympics**, officially the **XIII Olympic Winter Games** and also known as **Lake Placid 1980**, were an international multi-sport event held from February 13 to 24, 1980, in Lake Placid, New York, United States.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Lake Placid was elected as the host city for the 1980 Winter Games at the 75th International Olympic Committee (IOC) Session in Vienna, Austria, in 1974.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] This marked the second time the Upstate New York village hosted the Winter Games, after 1932.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The only other candidate city to bid for the 1980 games, Vancouver–Garibaldi, withdrew before the final vote.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Some venues from the 1932 Games were renovated for use in the 1980 Games, and events were held at the Olympic Center, Whiteface Mountain, Mt.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Van Hoevenberg Olympic Bobsled Run, the Olympic Ski Jumps, the Cascade Cross Country Ski Center, and the Lake Placid High School Speed Skating Oval.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Games were a success in terms of sport, but the organization was criticized because of numerous transport problems.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The 1980 Games were the last to take place in a city of less than 15,000 inhabitants.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Winter Olympics brought together 1,072 athletes from 37 countries to take part in six sports and 10 disciplines comprising a total of 38 official events (one more than in 1976).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] People's Republic of China, Cyprus, and Costa Rica participated in the Winter Olympic Games for the first time.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] American speed skater Eric Heiden set the record for most medals for an athlete in one edition of the Winter Olympic Games after he medaled in all five speed skating events.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Olympic ice hockey tournament saw the young American team defeat the heavily favored Soviet professionals in what became known as the *Miracle on Ice*, on their way to the gold medal.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] In the other disciplines, Soviet Nikolaj Zimjatov won three gold medals in cross-country skiing and the Liechtenstein skier Hanni Wenzel won her country's first two gold medals in alpine skiing.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Soviet Union finished first in the medal standings, with ten gold medals, while East Germany won the most medals overall, 23.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The United States was third on both counts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] After Lake Placid hosted the 1932 Olympic Winter Games, the community continued to bid on upcoming editions of the Games, submitting seven total bid attempts, including 1948, 1952, and 1956.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Three of these were supported by the United States Olympic Committee and presented to the International Olympic Committee: 1968, 1976, and 1980.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Until 1980, each of the bid attempts failed, either due to falling short of gaining support at the national level, or during the IOC vote.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] When Denver withdrew after being selected to host the 1976 Winter Games, the USOC initially supported Salt Lake City to replace Denver.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] But on January 26, 1973, the Salt Lake City bid collapsed due to unsecured financial backing and discontent by Utah residents.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Lake Placid and the USOC submitted a late bid to host the 1976 Games to the IOC in February 1973, as there was a risk that the selection process would be canceled due to the lack of interested parties.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The IOC selected Innsbruck, Austria, to host the 1976 Games in place of Denver, with Lake Placid finishing as the runner-up.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] IOC President Lord Killanin later stated that members of the IOC executive favored the Austrian bid as a way to "make peace with the people of Austria" over the decision in 1972 to declare Austrian skiing star Karl Schranz ineligible for the games as a professional athlete.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Undeterred, Lake Placid re-sent the same campaign materials that were originally used for the 1976 bid to the United States Olympic Committee on November 20, 1973, and made the official bid in September 1974.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The United States Olympic Committee, embarrassed by Denver's 1976 withdrawal, required Lake Placid's bid to be widely supported by residents and government.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Lake Placid also secured the support of the environmental groups Sierra Club and Adirondack Mountain Club.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Three other cities declared themselves candidates for the 1980 Winter Games: Vancouver—Garibaldi (Canada), Lahti (Finland), and Chamonix (France).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The bids for Lahti and Chamonix were withdrawn early in the bid process, and Vancouver (the latter hosted the 2010 games), which was unable to obtain the support of the Government of British Columbia, withdrew its candidacy on October 4, 1974.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The members of the IOC awarded the 1980 Winter Games to Lake Placid on October 23, 1974, during the 75th IOC Session in Vienna.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Games took place in the shadow of the Cold War with a number of other complex international events occurring in the leadup to the games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] In November 1979, sixty-two Americans were taken hostage at the United States embassy in Tehran by Iranian militants, a situation that would not resolve until after the Games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] In December 1979, the Soviet Union began the invasion of Afghanistan, which led to United States President Jimmy Carter calling for the international boycott of the 1980 Summer Games in Moscow.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Western governments first considered the idea of boycotting the Moscow 1980 Summer Olympics in response to the situation in Afghanistan at the December 20, 1979, meeting of NATO representatives.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The idea was not completely new to the world: in the mid-1970s, proposals for an Olympic boycott circulated widely among human rights activists and groups as a sanction for Soviet violations of human rights.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] At that time, very few member governments expressed interest in the proposal.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] However, the idea gained popularity in early January 1980 when Soviet nuclear scientist and dissident Andrei Sakharov called for a boycott.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] On January 14, 1980, the Carter Administration joined Sakharov's appeal and set a deadline by which the Soviet Union must pull out of Afghanistan or face the consequences, including an international boycott of the games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] On January 26, 1980, Canadian Prime Minister Joe Clark announced that Canada, like the US, would boycott the Olympic Games if Soviet forces did not leave Afghanistan by February 20, 1980.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Carter also proposed moving the Olympics to Greece on a permanent basis to eliminate the issue of politicization of the Games' hosting, but the IOC rejected the idea.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Ultimately, 66 nations boycotted the 1980 Summer Olympics, but this did not impact the Lake Placid Games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Another ongoing international situation was the conflict between the People's Republic of China and Taiwan.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Taiwan competed under the name of "Republic of China" and with its national flag until the 1976 Winter Games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] In October 1979, the IOC recognized the Olympic Committee of the People's Republic of China after threats from China to withdraw from the Games, and forced Taiwan to take the name "Chinese Taipei" and to adopt a new flag for the 1980 Games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The decision was appealed to a Swiss court and was upheld on January 15, 1980.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Taiwanese delegation refused to comply with the IOC's decision and arrived at the Olympic Village with the same flag and the same name as before.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] After being refused entry, the Taiwan team canceled its participation in the Games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The People's Republic of China, which threatened to withdraw if Taiwan participated under the name of "Republic of China", took part in its first Olympic Games since 1952 and the first Winter Games in its history.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Olympic Organizing Committee (LPOOC) was established as a not-for-profit corporation in December 1974.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Its board of directors was made up of 48 people, with a 13-member executive board.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Ron MacKenzie, who was instrumental in developing the region and securing the Games, was the chair of the organizing committee when it was founded.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] He died in December 1978, fourteen months before the start of the Games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Bernard Fell was the chairman of the board of directors and Art Devlin was the vice-chairman.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The LPOOC's vision for the Games was a simple Games that would return to the basics of the Olympic movement.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The budget for the 1980 Winter Olympic Games grew from an initial projection of US$30 million, to a total of US$168.7 million.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The cost of the games was financed by three parties, the federal government ($82.7 million), the State of New York ($32.4 million), and the organizing committee ($53.6 million).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] In the 2016 study of cost overruns at Olympic Games at Oxford University, researchers found the Lake Placid Winter Olympic Games had the largest cost overruns of any Winter Games at 324 percent above the planned cost.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The budget overruns were attributed to environmental protection measures, additional work undertaken to modernize existing facilities, overly optimistic cost estimates, and inflation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Games ended with a deficit of $8.5 million.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] After a request for funds and the authorities' refusal, the organizing committee saw no other option but to declare bankruptcy, but in January 1981 the Governor of New York announced that the remaining deficit would be paid by New York State.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Additional costs included transport improvements totaling $4.8 million, the extension of the electricity and hydroelectric network at $2.7 million, and construction for the headquarters of the New York State Police at $3.8 million.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] In addition, $8 million was allocated for security costs.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The expenses of the organizing committee were mainly administrative totaling $48.1 million.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The increasing costs for the Games and charges of nepotism and mismanagement resulted in a federal auditor investigating the LPOOC.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Public questions regarding accounting practices and contract awards resulted in the LPOOC's marketing director being replaced.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Further scrutiny came when another director was asked to resign when it became public that the individual had not filed income taxes for a number of years.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The company awarded the food management contract for the Games came under federal investigation for associations with organized crime.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Revenue for the LPOOC came primarily from sponsorship contracts signed with more than 200 companies totaling around $30 million in cash, goods or services, and from the sale of broadcasting rights totaling $21 million and included $8 million donated to the IOC.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Around 550,000 tickets were distributed for the 1980 Winter Olympic Games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Ticket distribution to the public included different regions of the United States (65.8%), Canada (6%), and other countries (8.2%).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The remainder was distributed among sponsors and suppliers (8.7%), the US Olympic Committee, the organizing committee, authorities, donors, and authorized companies (10.1%), or kept in reserve (1.2%).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The public prices for tickets ranged from $15 to $70.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Security for the Lake Placid Winter Games was provided by the New York State Police and 26 other agencies including the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The organizing committee also hired the private security company Pinkerton National Detective Agency.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The security headquarters were located at Ray Brook, which also was the site of the Olympic Village.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Police officers were trained in hostage negotiation techniques and various sensors were installed to detect any terrorist attack.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] A four-meter double barrier was erected surrounding the Olympic Village.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Winter Games were plagued with transportation problems complicating the planning and operations of the Games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The small mountain community did not have the accommodations or resources to handle the expected 50,000 spectators each day.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Most of the accommodations within the community were reserved for Games officials and athletes' families, meaning spectators commuted as much as ninety miles (140 km) daily to attend events.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Anticipating these challenges, the LPOOC prohibited private cars from entering Lake Placid for the duration of the Games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Instead the LPOOC provided parking and a shuttle system to transport spectators to the competition venues, and hired 60 taxis and 300 coaches, instead of the 450 initially planned, to be available to athletes, coaches, officials, and VIPs.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The first evidence that the Games would be plagued with transportation issues came a year earlier, at the pre-Olympic ski jumping competition in February 1979, which saw spectators create an eleven-mile (18 km) traffic jam.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Once the Games started, the inadequate transportation planning was evident quickly as American and Soviet athletes arrived late for the opening ceremony.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Throughout the Games, the main street of Lake Placid was often blocked by traffic jams, and journalists, spectators, and athletes found long waits at bus stops.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Spectators were often left stranded, either missing events or unable to return home from events.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] After five days, Governor Hugh Carey declared a partial state of emergency to address the issues.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The LPOOC attributed the transportation challenges to, among other things, the lack of communication with transport companies and the state government.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The emblem of the 1980 Olympic Winter Games contained several symbols.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The right part was reminiscent of the mountains surrounding Lake Placid and the left part was a stylized Ionic column that referred to the Ancient Olympics.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The indentation at the top of the column represented two basins symbolizing the two editions of the Games organized in Lake Placid.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] On the Games poster, the Olympic rings overhung this emblem.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The former Will Rogers Memorial Hospital was briefly used as press headquarters.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The site was considered ideal for the available infrastructure from the 1932 Winter Olympics, most notably the Bobsleigh run.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The existing facilities meant the Olympics could be staged on a reasonable budget and with limited environmental impact.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] It was not just a matter of convenience, either, according to Lake Placid's congressman, Representative Robert McEwen.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] "It is no secret to us in America that the measure of federal support given to athletes in Communist countries (so that they win medals and improve the countries' image abroad) is on a level unknown to us here in America," he told Congress.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The local Olympic committee needed congressional approval for funding to build the Olympic Village.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Congress required an after-use contract for facilities, and it was agreed that the Olympic Village would be built in accordance to Federal Bureau of Prisons needs.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Following the Olympic Games, it was repurposed for Federal Correctional Institution, Ray Brook.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1980 Winter Games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Cyprus made its Olympic debut at the games.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The People's Republic of China and Costa Rica both made their Winter Olympic debut.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The Republic of China refused to attend both the Summer Games in Montreal, the Winter Games in Lake Placid, and the Summer Games in Moscow over the IOC's recognition of the People's Republic of China as "China", and its request for the Republic of China to compete as "Chinese Taipei".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The PRC, on the other hand, returned to the Olympics for the first time since 1952 and made its Winter Olympic debut, although it then boycotted the 1980 Moscow Summer Olympics.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] Roni was the Olympic mascot of the Games, created by Don Moss.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The mascot was a raccoon, which is a familiar animal from the mountainous region of the Adirondacks where Lake Placid is situated.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The name Roni came from the word *raccoon* in Iroquoian, the language of the native people from the region of the State of New York and Lake Placid, and was chosen by Lake Placid school children.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/1980-winter-olympics] The official theme song for the 1980 Winter Olympics was "Give It All You Got" by the American flugelhorn player Chuck Mangione, who performed the song (along with the song "Piña Colada") live at the Closing Ceremony, with the Hamilton Philharmonic Orchestra (Canada).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] An **airbag** or **supplemental inflatable restraint** is a vehicle occupant-restraint system using a bag designed to inflate in milliseconds during a collision and then deflate afterwards.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] It consists of an airbag cushion, a flexible fabric bag, an inflation module, and an impact sensor.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The purpose of the airbag is to provide a vehicle occupant with soft cushioning and restraint during a collision.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] It can reduce injuries between the flailing occupant and the vehicle's interior.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The airbag provides an energy-absorbing surface between the vehicle's occupants and a steering wheel, instrument panel, body pillar, headliner, and windshield.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Modern vehicles may contain up to ten airbag modules in various configurations, including driver, passenger, side-curtain, seat-mounted, door-mounted, B- and C-pillar mounted side-impact, knee bolster, inflatable seat belt, and pedestrian airbag modules.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] During a crash, the vehicle's crash sensors provide crucial information to the airbag electronic controller unit (ECU), including collision type, angle, and severity of impact.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Using this information, the airbag ECU's crash algorithm determines if the crash event meets the criteria for deployment and triggers various firing circuits to deploy one or more airbag modules within the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Airbag module deployments are activated through a pyrotechnic process designed to be used once as a supplemental restraint system for the vehicle's seat belt systems.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Newer side-impact airbag modules consist of compressed-air cylinders that are triggered in the event of a side-on vehicle impact.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The first commercial designs were introduced in passenger automobiles during the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] These designs saw limited success and caused some fatalities.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Broad commercial adoption of airbags occurred in many markets during the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Airbags are considered "passive" restraints and act as a supplement to "active" restraints.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Because no action by a vehicle occupant is required to activate or use the airbag, it is considered a "passive" device.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] This is in contrast to seat belts, which are considered "active" devices because the vehicle occupant must act to enable them.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] This terminology is not related to active and passive safety, which are, respectively, systems designed to prevent collisions in the first place, and systems designed to minimize the effects of collisions once they occur.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In this use, a car Anti-lock braking system qualifies as an active-safety device, while both its seat belts and airbags qualify as passive-safety devices.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Terminological confusion can arise from the fact that passive devices and systems—those requiring no input or action by the vehicle occupant—can operate independently in an active manner; an airbag is one such device.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Vehicle safety professionals are generally careful in their use of language to avoid this sort of confusion.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] However, advertising principles sometimes prevent such semantic caution in the consumer marketing of safety features.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Further confusing the terminology, the aviation safety community uses the terms "active" and "passive" in the *opposite* sense from the automotive industry.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The airbag "for the covering of aeroplane and other vehicle parts" traces its origins to a United States patent, submitted in 1919 by two dentists from Birmingham, Arthur Parrott and Harold Round.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Air-filled bladders were in use as early as 1951.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The airbag specifically for automobile use is credited independently to the American John W.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Hetrick, who filed for an airbag patent on 5 August 1952, that was granted #2,649,311 by the United States Patent Office on 18 August 1953.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] German patent #896,312 filed for by engineer Walter Linderer on 6 October 1951 was issued on 12 November 1953, approximately three months after American John Hetrick.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The airbags proposed by Hetrick and Linderer were based on compressed air released by a spring, bumper contact, or by the driver.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Later research during the 1960s showed that compressed air could not inflate the mechanical airbags fast enough to ensure maximum safety, leading to the current chemical and electrical airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In patent applications, manufacturers sometimes use the term "inflatable occupant restraint systems".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Hetrick was an industrial engineer and member of the United States Navy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] His airbag design, however, only came about when he combined his experiences working with navy torpedoes with his desire to protect his family on the road.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Despite working with the major automobile manufacturers of his time, Hetrick was unable to attract investment.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Although airbags are now required in every automobile sold in the United States, Hetrick's 1951 patent filing serves as an example of a "valuable" invention with little economic value to its inventor.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Its first commercial use was not implemented until after the patent expired in 1971, at which point the airbag was installed in a few experimental Ford cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1964, a Japanese automobile engineer, Yasuzaburou Kobori (小堀保三郎), started developing an airbag "safety net" system.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] His design harnessed an explosive to inflate an airbag, for which he was later awarded patents in 14 countries.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] He died in 1975, before seeing the widespread adoption of airbag systems.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1967, a breakthrough in developing airbag crash sensors came when Allen K.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Breed invented a ball-in-tube mechanism for crash detection.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Under his system, an electromechanical sensor with a steel ball attached to a tube by a magnet would inflate an airbag in under 30 milliseconds.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] A small explosion of sodium azide was used instead of compressed air during inflation for the first time.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Breed Corporation then marketed this innovation to Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] A similar "Auto-Ceptor" crash-restraint, developed by the Eaton, Yale & Towne company for Ford, was soon also offered as an automatic safety system in the United States, while the Italian Eaton-Livia company offered a variant with localized air cushions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In the early 1970s, General Motors began offering cars equipped with airbags, initially in government fleet-purchased 1973 Chevrolet Impala sedans.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] These cars came with a 1974-style Oldsmobile instrument panel and a unique steering wheel that contained the driver-side airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Two of these cars were crash tested after 20 years and the airbags deployed perfectly.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] An early example of the airbag cars survives as of 2009.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] GM's Oldsmobile Toronado was the first domestic U.S. vehicle to include a passenger airbag in 1973.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] General Motors marketed its first airbag modules under the "Air Cushion Restraint System" name, or ACRS.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The automaker discontinued the option for its 1977 model year, citing a lack of consumer interest.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Ford and GM then spent years lobbying against air-bag requirements, claiming that the devices were unfeasible and inappropriate.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Chrysler made driver-side airbags standard on 1988 and 1989 models, but airbags did not become widespread in American cars until the early 1990s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Airbags for passenger cars were introduced in the United States in the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] When seat-belt usage rates in the country were quite low compared to modern-day, Ford built experimental cars with airbags in 1971.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Allstate operated a fleet of 200 Mercury Montereys and showed the reliability of airbags as well as their operation in crash testing, which also was promoted by the insurance company in popular magazine advertisements.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] General Motors followed in 1973 using full-sized Chevrolet vehicles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The early fleet of experimental GM vehicles equipped with airbags experienced seven fatalities, one of which was later suspected to have been caused by the airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1974, GM made its ACRS system (which consisted of a padded lower dashboard and a passenger-side air bag) available as a regular production option (RPO code AR3) in full-sized Cadillac, Buick and Oldsmobile models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The GM cars from the 1970s equipped with ACRS had a driver-side airbag, and a driver-side knee restraint.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The passenger-side airbag protected both front passengers, and unlike most modern systems, integrated a knee and torso cushion while also having a dual-stage deployment dictated by force of the impact.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The cars equipped with ACRS had lap belts for all seating positions, but lacked shoulder belts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Shoulder belts were already mandatory in the United States on closed cars without airbags for the driver and outer front passenger, but GM chose to market its airbags as a substitute for shoulder belts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The early development of airbags coincided with international interest in automobile safety legislation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Some safety experts advocated a performance-based occupant-protection standard rather than one mandating a particular technical solution (which could rapidly become outdated and prove to not be a cost-effective approach).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Less emphasis was placed on other designs as countries successfully mandated seat belt restrictions, however.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The auto industry and research and regulatory communities have moved away from their initial view of the airbag as a seat-belt replacement, and the bags are now nominally designated as **supplemental restraint systems** (**SRS**) or supplemental inflatable restraints.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1981, Mercedes-Benz introduced the airbag in West Germany as an option on its flagship saloon model, S-Class (W126).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In the Mercedes system, the sensors automatically tensioned the seat belts to reduce occupants' motion on impact and then deployed the airbag on impact.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] This integrated the seat belts and the airbag into a restraint system, rather than the airbag being considered an alternative to the seat belt.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1987, the Porsche 944 Turbo became the first car to have driver and passenger airbags as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The Porsche 944 and 944S had this as an available option.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The same year also had the first airbag in a Japanese car, the Honda Legend.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1988, Chrysler became the first United States automaker to fit a driver-side airbag as standard equipment, which was offered in six different models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The following year, Chrysler became the first US auto manufacturer to offer driver-side airbags in all its new passenger models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Chrysler also began featuring the airbags in advertisements showing how the devices had saved lives that helped the public know the value of them and safety became a selling advantage in the late 1980s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] All versions of the Chrysler minivans came with airbags starting for the 1991 model year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1993, The Lincoln Motor Company boasted that all vehicles in their model line were equipped with dual airbags, one for the driver's side and another for the passenger's side.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The 1993 Jeep Grand Cherokee became the first SUV to offer a driver-side airbag when it was launched in 1992.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Driver and passenger airbags became standard equipment in all Dodge Intrepid, Eagle Vision, and Chrysler Concorde sedans ahead of any safety regulations.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Early 1993 saw the 4-millionth airbag-equipped Chrysler vehicle roll off the assembly line.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In October 1993, the Dodge Ram became the first pickup truck with a standard driver-side airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The first known collision between two airbag-equipped automobiles took place on 12 March 1990 in Virginia, USA.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] A 1989 Chrysler LeBaron crossed the center line and hit another 1989 Chrysler LeBaron in a head-on collision, causing both driver airbags to deploy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The drivers suffered only minor injuries despite extensive damage to the vehicles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The United States Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act of 1991 required passenger cars and light trucks built after 1 September 1998 to have airbags for the driver and the front passenger.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In the United States, NHTSA estimated that airbags had saved over 4,600 lives by 1 September 1999; however, the crash deployment experience of the early 1990s installations indicated that some fatalities and serious injuries were in fact caused by airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1998, NHTSA initiated new rules for advanced airbags that gave automakers more flexibility in devising effective technological solutions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The revised rules also required improved protection for occupants of different sizes regardless of whether they use seat belts, while minimizing the risk to infants, children, and other occupants caused by airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In Europe, airbags were almost unheard of until the early 1990s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Citroën, Fiat, Nissan, Hyundai, Peugeot, Renault, and Volkswagen followed shortly afterwards.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] By 1999, finding a new mass-market car without an airbag at least as optional equipment was difficult, and some late 1990s products, such as the Volkswagen Golf Mk4, also featured side airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The Peugeot 306 is one example of the European automotive mass-market evolution: starting in early 1993, most of these models did not even offer a driver's airbag as an option, but by 1999, even side airbags were available on several variants.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Audi was late to offer airbag systems on a broader scale, since even in the 1994 model year, its popular models did not offer airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Instead, the German automaker until then relied solely on its proprietary cable-based procon-ten restraint system.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Variable force-deployment front airbags were developed to help minimize injury from the airbag itself.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Many new cars in Latin America, including the Kia Rio, Kia Picanto, Hyundai Grand i10, Mazda 2, Chevrolet Spark and the Chevrolet Onix, are often sold without airbags, as neither airbags nor automatic braking systems in new cars are compulsory in many Latin American countries.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Some require the installation of a minimum of only two airbags in new cars which many in this market have.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The Citroën C4 provided the first "shaped" driver airbag, made possible by this car's unusual fixed-hub steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 2019, Honda announced it would introduce a new front passenger airbag technology.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Developed by Autoliv and Honda R&D in Ohio, United States, this new airbag design features three inflatable chambers connected across the front by a "noninflatable sail panel." The two outer chambers are larger than the middle chamber.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] When the airbag deploys, the sail panel cushions the occupant's head from the impact of hitting the airbag, and the three chambers hold the occupant's head in place, like a catcher's mitt.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The goal of the tri-chamber airbag is to help "arrest high-speed movement" of the head, thereby reducing the likelihood of concussion injuries in a collision.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The first vehicle to come with the tri-chamber airbag installed from the factory was in 2020 (for the 2021 model year) for the Acura TLX.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Honda hopes that the new technology will soon make its way to all vehicles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Mercedes began offering rear passengers protection in frontal collisions in September 2020 (for the 2021 model year) for the Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W223).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The W223 S-Class is the first car equipped with rear seat airbags that use gas to inflate supporting structures that unfold and extend a bag that fills with ambient air, instead of conventional fully gas-inflated airbags that are widely used in automotive airbag systems.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Essentially, two types of side airbags are commonly used today - the side-torso airbag and the side-curtain airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] More recently, center airbags are becoming more common in the European market.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Most vehicles equipped with side-curtain airbags also include side-torso airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] However, some, such as the Chevrolet Cobalt, 2007–09 model Chevrolet Silverado/GMC Sierra, and 2009–12 Dodge Ram do not feature the side-torso airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] From around 2000, side-impact airbags became commonplace on even low- to mid-range vehicles, such as the smaller-engined versions of the Ford Fiesta and Peugeot 206, and curtain airbags were also becoming regular features on mass-market cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The Toyota Avensis, launched in 2003, was the first mass-market car to be sold in Europe with nine airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Side-impact airbags or side-torso airbags are a category of airbags usually located in the seat or door panel, and inflate between the seat occupant and the door.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] These airbags are designed to reduce the risk of injury to the pelvic and lower abdomen regions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Most vehicles are now being equipped with different types of designs, to help reduce injury and ejection from the vehicle in rollover crashes.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] More recent side-airbag designs include a two-chamber system; a firmer lower chamber for the pelvic region and softer upper chamber for the ribcage.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Swedish company Autoliv AB was granted a patent on side-impact airbags, and they were first offered as an option in 1994 on the 1995 Volvo 850, and as standard equipment on all Volvo cars made after 1995.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1997, Saab introduced the first combined head and torso airbags with the launch of the Saab 9-5.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Some cars, such as the 2010 Volkswagen Polo Mk.5 have combined head- and torso-side airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] These are fitted in the backrest of the front seats and protect the head and the torso.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1997, the BMW 7 Series and 5 Series were fitted with tubular-shaped head side airbags (inflatable tubular structure), the "Head Protection System (HPS)" as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] This airbag was designed to offer head protection in side impact collisions and also maintained inflation for up to seven seconds for rollover protection.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] However, this tubular-shaped airbag design has been quickly replaced by an inflatable 'curtain' airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In May 1998, Toyota began offering a side-curtain airbag deploying from the roof on the Progrés.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1998, the Volvo S80 was given roof-mounted curtain airbags to protect both front and rear passengers.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Curtain airbags were then made standard equipment on all new Volvo cars from 2000 except for the first-generation C70, which received an enlarged side-torso airbag that also protects the head of front-seat occupants.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The second-generation C70 convertible received the world's first door-mounted, side-curtain airbags that deployed upwards.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Curtain airbags have been said to reduce brain injury or fatalities by up to 45% in a side impact with an SUV.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] These airbags come in various forms (e.g., tubular, curtain, door-mounted) depending on the needs of the application.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Many recent SUVs and MPVs have a long inflatable curtain airbag that protects all rows of seats.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In many vehicles, the curtain airbags are programmed to deploy during some/all frontal impacts to manage passenger kinetics (e.g. head hitting B-pillar on the rebound), especially in offset crashes such as the IIHS's small overlap crash test.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Roll-sensing curtain airbags are designed to stay inflated for a longer duration of time, cover a larger proportion of the window, and be deployed in a roll-over crash.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] They offer protection to occupants' heads and help to prevent ejection.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] SUVs and pickups are more likely to be equipped with RSCAs due to their higher probability of rolling over and often a switch can disable the feature in case the driver wants to take the vehicle off-road.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 2009, Toyota developed the first production rear-seat center airbag designed to reduce the severity of secondary injuries to rear passengers in a side collision.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] This system deploys from the rear center seat first appearing in on the Crown Majesta.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In late 2012, General Motors with supplier Takata introduced a front center airbag; it deploys from the driver's seat.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Hyundai Motor Group announced its development of a center-side airbag on September 18, 2019, installed inside the driver's seat.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Some Volkswagen vehicles in 2022 equipped with center airbags include the ID.3 and the Golf.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The Polestar 2 also includes a center airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Škoda makes center airbags standard equipment in cars and Honda wants to add center airbags to their advanced airbag system in 2023.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] With EuroNCAP updating its testing guidelines in 2020, European and Australian market vehicles increasingly use front-center airbags, rear torso airbags, and rear seat belt pre-tensioners.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The second driver-side and separate knee airbag was used in the Kia Sportage SUV and has been standard equipment since then.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The airbag is located beneath the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The Toyota Caldina introduced the first driver-side SRS knee airbag on the Japanese market in 2002.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Toyota Avensis became the first vehicle sold in Europe equipped with a driver's knee airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The EuroNCAP reported on the 2003 Avensis, "There has been much effort to protect the driver's knees and legs and a knee airbag worked well." Since then certain models have also included front-passenger knee airbags, which deploy near or over the glove compartment in a crash.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Knee airbags are designed to reduce leg injury.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The knee airbag has become increasingly common since 2000.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 2008, the new Toyota iQ microcar featured the first production rear-curtain shield airbag to protect the rear occupants' heads in the event of a rear-end impact.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Another feature of the Toyota iQ was a seat-cushion airbag in the passenger seat to prevent the pelvis from diving below the lap belt during a frontal impact or submarining.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Later Toyota models such as the Yaris added the feature to the driver's seat, as well.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The seat-belt airbag is designed to better distribute the forces experienced by a buckled person in a crash using an increased seat belt area.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] This is done to reduce possible injuries to the rib cage or chest of the belt wearer.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Cessna Aircraft also introduced seat belt airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Airbag(s) mounted to the exterior of vehicles, so-called "pedestrian airbags", are designed to reduce injuries in the event of a vehicle to a pedestrian collision.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] When a collision is detected the airbag will deploy and cover hard areas, such as a-pillars and bonnet edges, before they can be struck by the pedestrian.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] When introduced in 2012 the Volvo V40 included the world's first pedestrian airbag as standard.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] As a result, the V40 ranked highest (88%) in the EuroNCAP's pedestrian tests.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Suppliers of SRS airbags include Autoliv, Daicel, TRW, and JSS (which owns Breed, Key Safety Systems, and Takata).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The majority of impact sensors of airbags are manufactured by the Lanka Harness Company in Sri Lanka.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The airbags in the vehicle are controlled by a central airbag control unit (ACU), a specific type of ECU.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The ACU monitors several related sensors within the vehicle, including accelerometers, impact sensors, side (door) pressure sensors, wheel speed sensors, gyroscopes, brake pressure sensors, and seat occupancy sensors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Oftentimes, ACUs log this—and other—sensor data in a circular buffer and record it to onboard non-volatile memory, to provide a snapshot of the crash event for investigators.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] As such, an ACU frequently functions as the vehicle's event data recorder (EDR); not all EDRs are ACUs, and not all ACUs include EDR features.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] An ACU typically includes capacitors within its circuitry, so that the module remains powered and able to deploy the airbags if the vehicle's battery connection to the ACU is severed during a crash.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The bag itself and its inflation mechanism are concealed within the steering wheel boss (for the driver), or the dashboard (for the front passenger), behind plastic flaps or doors that are designed to tear open under the force of the bag inflating.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Once the requisite threshold has been reached or exceeded, the airbag control unit will trigger the ignition of a gas generator propellant to rapidly inflate a fabric bag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] As the vehicle occupant collides with and squeezes the bag, the gas escapes in a controlled manner through small vent holes.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The airbag's volume and the size of the vents in the bag are tailored to each vehicle type, to spread out the deceleration of (and thus force experienced by) the occupant over time and over the occupant's body, compared to a seat belt alone.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The signals from the various sensors are fed into the airbag control unit, which determines from them the angle of impact, the severity, or the force of the crash, along with other variables.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Depending on the result of these calculations, the ACU may also deploy various additional restraint devices, such as seat belt pre-tensioners, and/or airbags (including frontal bags for driver and front passenger, along with seat-mounted side bags, and "curtain" airbags which cover the side glass).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Each restraint device is typically activated with one or more pyrotechnic devices, commonly called an initiator or electric match.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The electric match, which consists of an electrical conductor wrapped in a combustible material, activates with a current pulse between 1 and 3 amps in less than 2 milliseconds.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] When the conductor becomes hot enough, it ignites the combustible material, which initiates the gas generator.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In a seat belt pre-tensioner, this hot gas is used to drive a piston that pulls the slack out of the seat belt.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In an airbag, the initiator is used to ignite solid propellant inside the airbag inflator.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The burning propellant generates inert gas which rapidly inflates the airbag in approximately 20 to 30 ms.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] An airbag must inflate quickly to be fully inflated by the time the forward-traveling occupant reaches its outer surface.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Typically, the decision to deploy an airbag in a frontal crash is made within 15 to 30 ms after the onset of the crash, and both the driver and passenger airbags are fully inflated within approximately 60 to 80 ms after the first moment of vehicle contact.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] If an airbag deploys too late or too slowly, the risk of occupant injury from contact with the inflating airbag may increase.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Since more distance typically exists between the passenger and the instrument panel, the passenger airbag is larger and requires more gas to fill it.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Older airbag systems contained a mixture of sodium azide (NaN3), KNO3, and SiO2.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] A typical driver-side airbag contains approximately 50–80 grams (1.8–2.8 oz) of NaN3, with the larger passenger-side airbag containing about 250 grams (8.8 oz).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Within about 40 milliseconds of impact, all these components react in three separate reactions that produce nitrogen gas.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The reactions, in order, are as follows.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The first two reactions create 4 molar equivalents of nitrogen gas, and the third converts the remaining reactants to relatively inert potassium silicate and sodium silicate.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] There are ongoing efforts to find alternative compounds so that airbags have less toxic reactants.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The reaction of the Sr complex nitrate, (SrOC(N2H3)2·(NO3)2) of carbohydrazide (SrCDH) with various oxidizing agents results in the evolution of N2 and CO2 gases.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The N2 and CO2 gases evolved made up 99% of all gases evolved.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Nearly all of the starting materials will not decompose until reaching temperatures of 500 °C (932 °F) or higher, so this could be a viable option as an airbag gas generator.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Since airbags deploy only once and deflate quickly after the initial impact, they will not be beneficial during a subsequent collision.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In vehicles equipped with a rollover sensing system, accelerometers, and gyroscopes are used to sense the onset of a rollover event.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] If a rollover event is determined to be imminent, side-curtain airbags are deployed to help protect the occupant from contact with the side of the vehicle interior, and also to help prevent occupant ejection as the vehicle rolls over.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] International regulations are performance-based, rather than technology-based, so airbag deployment threshold is a function of overall vehicle design.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Unlike crash tests into barriers, real-world crashes typically occur at angles other than directly into the front of the vehicle, and the crash forces usually are not evenly distributed across the front of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Consequently, the relative speed between a striking and struck vehicle required to deploy the airbag in a real-world crash can be much higher than an equivalent barrier crash.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Because airbag sensors measure deceleration, the vehicle speed is not a good indicator of whether an airbag should be deployed.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Airbags can deploy due to the vehicle's undercarriage striking a low object protruding above the roadway due to the resulting deceleration.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The airbag sensor is a MEMS accelerometer, which is a small integrated circuit with integrated micromechanical elements.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The microscopic mechanical element moves in response to rapid deceleration, and this motion causes a change in capacitance, which is detected by the electronics on the chip that then sends a signal to fire the airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The most common MEMS accelerometer in use is the ADXL-50 by Analog Devices, but there are other MEMS manufacturers as well.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Initial attempts using mercury switches did not work well.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Before MEMS, the primary system used to deploy airbags was called a "rolamite".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] A rolamite is a mechanical device, consisting of a roller suspended within a tensioned band.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] As a result of the particular geometry and material properties used, the roller is free to translate with little friction or hysteresis.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] This device was developed at Sandia National Laboratories.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Rolamite and similar macro-mechanical devices were used in airbags until the mid-1990s after which they were universally replaced with MEMS.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Nearly all airbags are designed to automatically deploy in the event of a vehicle fire when temperatures reach 150–200 °C (302–392 °F).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] This safety feature, often termed auto-ignition, helps to ensure that such temperatures do not cause an explosion of the entire airbag module.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Today, airbag triggering algorithms are much more complex, being able to adapt the deployment speed to the crash conditions, and prevent unnecessary deployments.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The algorithms are considered valuable intellectual property.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Experimental algorithms may take into account such factors as the weight of the occupant, the seat location, and seat belt use, as well as even attempt to determine if a baby seat is present.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] When the frontal airbags are to deploy, a signal is sent to the gas generator/inflator unit within the airbag control unit.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] An igniter starts a rapid chemical reaction generating primarily nitrogen gas (N2) to fill the airbag making it deploy through the module cover.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Some airbag technologies use compressed nitrogen or argon gas with a pyrotechnic operated valve ("hybrid gas generator"), while other technologies use various energetic propellants.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Although propellants containing the highly toxic sodium azide (NaN3) were common in early inflator designs, little to no toxic sodium azide has been found on used airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The azide-containing pyrotechnic gas generators contain a substantial amount of the propellant.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The driver-side airbag would contain a canister containing about 50 grams (1.8 oz) of sodium azide.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The passenger side container holds about 200 grams (7.1 oz) of sodium azide.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] From the onset of the crash, the entire deployment and inflation process is about 0.04 seconds.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Because vehicles change speed so quickly in a crash, airbags must inflate rapidly to reduce the risk of the occupant hitting the vehicle's interior.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Advanced airbag technologies are being developed to tailor airbag deployment to the severity of the crash, the size, and posture of the vehicle occupant, belt usage, and how close that person is to the actual airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Many of these systems use multi-stage inflators that deploy less forcefully in stages in moderate crashes than in very severe crashes.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Occupant sensing devices let the airbag control unit know if someone is occupying a seat adjacent to an airbag, the mass/weight of the person, whether a seat belt or child restraint is being used, and whether the person is forward in the seat and close to the airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Based on this information and crash severity information, the airbag is deployed at either a high force level, a less forceful level, or not at all.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Adaptive airbag systems may utilize multi-stage airbags to adjust the pressure within the airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The greater the pressure within the airbag, the more force the airbag will exert on the occupants as they come in contact with it.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] These adjustments allow the system to deploy the airbag with a moderate force for most collisions; reserving the maximum force airbag only for the severest of collisions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Additional sensors to determine the location, weight or relative size of the occupants may also be used.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Information regarding the occupants and the severity of the crash are used by the airbag control unit, to determine whether airbags should be suppressed or deployed, and if so, at various output levels.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] A chemical reaction produces a burst of nitrogen to inflate the bag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Once an airbag deploys, deflation begins immediately as the gas escapes through vent(s) in the fabric (or, as it is sometimes called, the cushion) and cools.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Deployment is frequently accompanied by the release of dust-like particles, and gases in the vehicle's interior (called effluent).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Most of this dust consists of cornstarch, french chalk, or talcum powder, which are used to lubricate the airbag during deployment.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Newer designs produce effluent primarily consisting of harmless talcum powder/cornstarch and nitrogen gas.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In older designs using an azide-based propellant (usually NaN3), varying amounts of sodium hydroxide nearly always are initially present.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In small amounts this chemical can cause minor irritation to the eyes and/or open wounds; however, with exposure to air, it quickly turns into sodium bicarbonate (baking soda).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] However, this transformation is not 100% complete, and invariably leaves residual amounts of hydroxide ions from NaOH.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Depending on the type of airbag system, potassium chloride may also be present.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] For most people, the only effect the dust may produce is some minor irritation of the throat and eyes.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Generally, minor irritations only occur when the occupant remains in the vehicle for many minutes with the windows closed and no ventilation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] However, some people with asthma may develop a potentially lethal asthmatic attack from inhaling the dust.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Because of the airbag exit flap design of the steering wheel boss and dashboard panel, these items are not designed to be recoverable if an airbag deploys, meaning that they have to be replaced if the vehicle has not been written off in a collision.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Moreover, the dust-like particles and gases can cause irreparable cosmetic damage to the dashboard and upholstery, meaning that minor collisions that result in the deployment of airbags can be costly, even if there are no injuries and there is only minor damage to the vehicle structure.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] On 11 July 1984, the United States government amended Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 208 (FMVSS 208) to require cars produced after 1 April 1989 to be equipped with a passive restraint for the driver.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] An airbag or an automatic seat belt would meet the requirements of the standard.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Airbag introduction was stimulated by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] However, airbags were not mandatory on light trucks until 1997.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 1998, FMVSS 208 was amended to require dual front airbags, and reduced-power, second-generation airbags were also mandated.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] This was due to the injuries caused by first-generation airbags, though FMVSS 208 continues to require that bags be engineered and calibrated to be able to "save" the life of an *unbelted* 50th-percentile size and weight "male" crash test dummy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The technical performance and validation requirements for the inflator assembly used in airbag modules are specified in SAE USCAR 24–2.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Some countries outside North America adhere to internationalized European ECE vehicle and equipment regulations rather than the United States Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] ECE airbags are generally smaller and inflate less forcefully than United States airbags because the ECE specifications are based on *belted* crash test dummies.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The Euro NCAP vehicle safety rating encourages manufacturers to take a comprehensive approach to occupant safety; a good rating can only be achieved by combining airbags with other safety features.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Almost every new car sold in Europe is equipped with front and side airbags, but in the European Union in 2020 and in the United Kingdom, and most other developed countries there is no direct legal requirement for new cars to feature airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Ecuador requires dual front airbags in new car models since 2013.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Since January 2014, except for micro vehicles, all new cars made or imported in Argentina must have front airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Since 1 January 2014, all new cars sold in Brazil must have dual front airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Since July 2014, all new cars sold in Uruguay must have dual front airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Since December 2016, all new cars sold in Chile must have dual front airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Since 1 January 2017, all cars made or imported in Colombia must have dual front airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Since 1 January 2020, all new cars sold in Mexico must have dual front airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] On 5 March 2021, the Indian Ministry of Road Transport and Highways mandated that all new vehicle models introduced in India after 1 April 2021 have dual front airbags; the regulation also requires that all existing models be equipped with dual front airbags by 31 August 2021.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] India also mandated that all passenger vehicles sold after October 2023 must have a minimum of six airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Inadvertent airbag deployment while a vehicle is being serviced can result in serious injury, and an improperly installed or defective airbag unit may fail to operate as intended.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] For this reason, individuals servicing vehicles, as well as first responders, are required to account for the fact that some airbag control systems may remain powered for up to 30 minutes after a vehicle's battery has been disconnected.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In some countries, the sale, transport, handling, and servicing of airbags and related components are subject to legal restrictions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In Germany, for example, airbags are regulated as hazardous explosive devices, and only trained auto mechanics are permitted to service airbag systems.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Automaker policies regarding the service life of undeployed airbags vary.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Some manufacturers, such as Mercedes-Benz, have historically recommended replacement after a specified period to ensure reliability.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Certain Škoda vehicles have indicated an airbag service life of approximately 14 years from the date of manufacture, after which replacement may be uneconomical relative to the vehicle’s value.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] By contrast, Volvo has stated that airbags are designed to last for the lifetime of the vehicle, although this is not presented as an absolute guarantee of performance.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Although the millions of installed airbags in use have an excellent safety record, some limitations on their ability to protect car occupants exist.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The original implementation of front airbags did little to protect against side collisions, which can be more dangerous than frontal collisions because the protective crumple zone in front of the passenger compartment is completely bypassed.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Side airbags and protective airbag curtains are increasingly being required in modern vehicles to protect against this very common category of collisions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Airbags are designed to deploy once only, so are ineffective if any further collisions occur after an initial impact.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Multiple impacts may occur during rollovers or other incidents involving multiple collisions, such as many multivehicle collisions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] An extremely dangerous situation occurs during "underride collisions", in which a passenger vehicle collides with the rear of a tractor-trailer lacking a rear underride guard, or hits the side of such a trailer not equipped with a side underride guard.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] The platform bed of a typical trailer is roughly at the head height of a seated adult occupant of a typical passenger car.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] This means not much of a barrier exists between a head and the edge of the trailer platform, except a glass windshield.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In an underride collision, the car's crush zones designed to absorb collision energy are completely bypassed, and the airbags may not deploy in time because the car does not decelerate appreciably until the windshield and roof pillars have already impacted the trailer bed.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Even delayed inflation of airbags may be useless because of major intrusion into the passenger space, leaving occupants at high risk of major head trauma or decapitation in even low-speed collisions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Western European standards for underride guards have been stricter than North American standards, which typically have allowed grandfathering of older equipment that may still be on the road for decades.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Typical airbag systems are completely disabled by turning off the ignition key.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Unexpected turnoffs usually also disable the engine, power steering, and power brakes, and can be the direct cause of a collision.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] If a violent collision occurs, the disabled airbags will not deploy to protect vehicle occupants.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] In 2014, General Motors admitted to concealing information about fatal collisions caused by defective ignition switches that would abruptly shut down a car (including its airbags).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p01] Between 13 and 74 deaths have been directly attributed to this defect, depending on how the fatalities are classified.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Under some rare conditions, airbags can injure and in some very rare instances kill vehicle occupants.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] To provide crash protection for occupants not wearing seat belts, United States airbag designs trigger much more forcefully than airbags designed to the international ECE standards used in most other countries.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Recent "smart" airbag controllers can recognize if a seat belt is used, and alter the airbag cushion deployment parameters accordingly.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] In 1990, the first automotive fatality attributed to an airbag was reported.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] TRW produced the first gas-inflated airbag in 1994, with sensors and low inflation-force bags becoming common soon afterward.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Dual-depth (also known as dual-stage) airbags appeared on passenger cars in 1998.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] By 2005, deaths related to airbags had declined, with no adult deaths and two child deaths attributed to airbags that year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] However, injuries remain fairly common in collisions with airbag deployment.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Serious injuries are less common, but severe or fatal injuries can occur to vehicle occupants very near an airbag or in direct contact when it deploys.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Such injuries may be sustained by unconscious drivers slumped over the steering wheel, unrestrained or improperly restrained occupants who slide forward in the seat during precrash braking, and properly belted drivers sitting very close to the steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] A US study showed that the risk for a serious head injury occurring is 5.495% while travelling 40–48 km/h (25–30 mph).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The risk is reduced for passengers to 4.435%.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] This risk is lowered by 80.5% to 1.073% when using an airbag.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The risk for passengers is lowered by 82% to 0.797%.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The tests with the airbags were done at 56 km/h (35 mph), 8–16 km/h (5–10 mph) faster than the tests without air bags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] There is a 15.45% risk of serious injury to unprotected occupants at 48–56 km/h (30–35 mph), this drops to 4.68% with protected occupants.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] This is a 69.7% decrease in change of serious injury, with the airbags deploying 96.1% of the time.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Improvements in sensing and gas-generator technology have allowed the development of third-generation airbag systems that can adjust their deployment parameters to the size, weight, position, and restraint status of the occupant.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] These improvements have demonstrated a reduced injury risk factor for small adults and children, who had an increased risk of injury with first-generation airbag systems.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] One model of airbags made by the Takata Corporation used ammonium nitrate–based gas-generating compositions in airbag inflators instead of the more stable, but more expensive compound tetrazole.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The ammonium nitrate-based inflators have a flaw where old inflators with long-term exposure to hot and humid climate conditions could rupture during deployment, projecting metal shards through the airbag and into the driver.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] As of December 2022, the defect has caused 33 deaths worldwide, with up to 24 in the U.S. and the remaining in Australia and Malaysia.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) recalled over 33 million vehicles in May 2015, and fined Takata $70 million in November 2015.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Toyota, Mazda, and Honda have said that they will not use ammonium-nitrate inflators.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] In June 2017, Takata filed for bankruptcy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] From 1990 to 2000, the United States NHTSA identified 175 fatalities caused by airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] About 3.3 million airbag deployments have occurred during that interval, and the agency estimates more than 6,377 lives were saved and countless injuries were prevented.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] A rear-facing infant restraint put in the front seat of a vehicle places an infant's head close to the airbag, which can cause severe head injuries or death if the airbag deploys.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Some modern cars include a switch to disable the front-passenger airbag, in case a child-supporting seat is used there (although not in Australia, where rear-facing child seats are prohibited in the front where an airbag is fitted).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] In vehicles with side airbags, it is dangerous for occupants to lean against the windows, doors, and pillars, or to place objects between themselves and the side of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Articles hung from a vehicle's clothes hanger hooks can be hazardous if the vehicle's side-curtain airbags are deployed.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] A seat-mounted airbag may also cause internal injury if the occupant leans against the door.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The aerospace industry and the United States government have applied airbag technologies for many years.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] NASA and United States Department of Defense have incorporated airbag systems in various aircraft and spacecraft applications as early as the 1960s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The first use of airbags for landing were Luna 9 and Luna 13.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] As with later missions, these would use the airbags to bounce along the surface, absorbing landing energy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The Mars Pathfinder lander employed an innovative airbag landing system, supplemented with aerobraking, parachute, and solid rocket landing thrusters.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] This prototype successfully tested the concept, and the two Mars Exploration Rover Mission landers employed similar landing systems.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The Beagle 2 Mars lander also tried to use airbags for landing; the landing was successful, and the lander touched down safely, but several of the spacecraft's solar panels failed to deploy, thereby disabling the spacecraft.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The Boeing Starliner uses six airbags to cushion the ground landing of the crewed capsule.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Airbags have also been used on military fixed-wing aircraft, such as the escape crew capsule of the F-111 Aardvark.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The United States Army has incorporated airbags in its UH-60A/L Black Hawk and OH-58D Kiowa Warrior helicopter fleets.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The Cockpit Air Bag System (CABS) consists of forward and lateral airbags, and an inflatable tubular structure (on the OH-58D only) with an Electronic Crash Sensor Unit (ECSU).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] The CABS system was developed by the United States Army Aviation Applied Technology Directorate, through a contract with Simula Safety Systems (now BAE Systems).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] It is the first conventional airbag system for occupant injury prevention (worldwide) designed and developed and placed in service for an aircraft, and the first specifically for helicopter applications.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] In the mid-1970s, the UK Transport Research Laboratory tested several types of motorcycle airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] In 2006 Honda introduced the first production motorcycle airbag safety system on its Gold Wing motorcycle.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Honda claims that sensors in the front forks can detect a severe frontal collision and decide when to deploy the airbag, absorbing some of the forward energy of the rider and reducing the velocity at which the rider may be thrown from the motorcycle.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] More commonly, air bag vests – either integrated into the motorcyclist's jacket or worn over it – have started to become used by regular riders on the street.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] MotoGP has made it compulsory since 2018 for riders to wear suits with integrated airbags.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Similarly, companies such as Helite and Hit-Air have commercialized equestrian airbags, which attach to the saddle and are worn by the rider.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/airbag-p02] Other sports, particularly skiing and snowboarding, have started introducing airbag safety mechanisms.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] The **American Antiquarian Society** (**AAS**), located in Worcester, Massachusetts, is a learned society and a national research library of pre-twentieth-century American history and culture.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] Founded in 1812, it is the oldest historical society in the United States with a national focus.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] Its main building, known as Antiquarian Hall, is a U.S.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] National Historic Landmark in recognition of this legacy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] The mission of the AAS is to collect, preserve and make available for study all printed records of what is now known as the United States of America.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] This includes materials from the first European settlement through the year 1900.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] The collections of the AAS contain over four million books, pamphlets, newspapers, periodicals, graphic arts materials and manuscripts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] The Society is estimated to hold copies of two-thirds of the total books known to have been printed in what is now the United States from the establishment of the first press in 1640 through the year 1820; many of these volumes are exceedingly rare and a number of them are unique.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] Historic materials from all fifty U.S. states, most of Canada and the British West Indies are included in the AAS repository.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] An act of congress requires that one copy of the journals of the Senate and of the House of Representatives along with other documents are to be transmitted to the Governor of Massachusetts for the use and benefit of the Society.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] One of the more notable volumes held by the Society is a copy of the first book printed in America, the Bay Psalm Book.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] AAS has one of the largest collections of newspapers printed in America through 1876, with more than two million issues in its collection.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] On the initiative of Isaiah Thomas, the AAS was founded on October 24, 1812, through an act of the Massachusetts General Court.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] It was the third historical society established in America, and the first to be national in its scope.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] Isaiah Thomas started the collection with approximately 8,000 books from his personal library.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] The first library building was erected in 1820 in downtown Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] In 1853, the Society moved its collections to a larger building at the corner of Highland Street, also in Worcester.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] This building was later abandoned and another new building was constructed.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] Designed by Winslow, Bigelow & Wadsworth, the Georgian Revival building was completed in 1910 and stands on the corner of Park Avenue and Salisbury Street.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] There have been several additions to this building to accommodate the growing collection.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] The most recent addition was completed in 2019 and created room for an updated HVAC system, conservation lab, and multi-use learning lab.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] AAS was presented with the 2013 National Humanities Medal by President Obama in a ceremony at the White House.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] As part of AAS's mission as a learned society, it offers a variety of public lectures and seminars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] One topic to which AAS dedicates significant academic energies is printing technology, especially in 18th century British North America.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] Since Isaiah Thomas was a newspaper man himself, he collected a large number of printed materials.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] With regard to printing, paper making, edition setting, and reprinting, not much had changed in European technology by the eighteenth century.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] It was not until the late eighteenth century that paper-making material began to evolve from a hand-woven cloth to an industrial pulp.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] AAS undertakes special efforts to preserve printed records from this time period, as the Society maintains an on-site conservation department with various sewing, cloth, and binding materials to aid in the preservation process.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] Over its two-hundred-year history, the Society has had 14 formal leaders who have shaped the organization's vision, collections, and day-to-day operations.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] Leadership roles at the AAS have historically overlapped in chronology, as different roles oversaw different aspects of the Society simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-antiquarian-society] The American Antiquarian Society's membership includes scholars, writers, journalists, historians, artists, filmmakers, collectors, American presidents, and civic leaders.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors' most similar competitors were those automakers that held similar annual sales levels, such as Studebaker, Packard, Kaiser Motors, and Willys-Overland.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Their largest competitors were the Big Three—Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] After periods of intermittent independent success, Renault acquired a significant interest in American Motors in 1979, and the company was ultimately acquired by Chrysler in 1987.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In January 1954, Nash-Kelvinator Corporation began the acquisition of the Hudson Motor Car Company (in what was called a merger).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The new corporation would be called the American Motors Corporation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] An earlier corporation with the same name, co-founded by Louis Chevrolet, had existed in Plainfield, New Jersey, from 1916 through 1922 before merging into the Bessemer–American Motors Corporation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The new company retained Hudson CEO A.E.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Barit as a consultant and he took a seat on the board of directors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Mason, the architect of the merger, believed that the survival of the U.S.'s remaining independent automakers depended on their joining to form one multiple-brand company capable of challenging the Big Three as an equal.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The "frantic 1953–54 Ford/GM price war" devastated the remaining "independent" automakers.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The reasons for the merger between Nash and Hudson included helping cut costs and strengthen their sales organizations to meet the intense competition expected from autos' Big Three.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] One quick result from the merger was the doubling up with Nash on purchasing and production, allowing Hudson to cut prices an average of $155 on the Wasp line, and up to $204 on the more expensive Hornet models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] After the merger, AMC had its first profitable quarter during the second three months of 1955, earning $1,592,307, compared to a loss of $3,848,667 during the same period in the previous year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Mason also entered into informal discussions with James J.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Nance of Packard to outline his strategic vision.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Interim plans were made for American Motors to buy Packard Ultramatic automatic transmissions and Packard V8 engines for certain American Motors products.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In July 1954, Packard acquired Studebaker.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The new Studebaker-Packard Corporation (S-P) made the new 320 cu in (5.2 L) Packard V8 engine and Packard's Ultramatic automatic transmission available to American Motors for its 1955 Nash Ambassador and Hudson Hornet models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Ironically, Romney had once been offered Nance's job.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In 1948, Romney received offers from Packard for the post of chief operating officer and from Nash for the number two position in the company.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Although the Packard offer would have paid more, Romney decided to work under Mason because he thought Nash had a brighter future.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Mason and Nance had agreed that S-P would endeavor to purchase parts from American Motors in return, but S-P did not do so.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] As the Packard engines and transmissions were comparatively expensive, American Motors began development of its own V8.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors also spent US$40 million developing its Double Safe Single Unit monocoque, which debuted in the 1956 model year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In mid-1956, the 352 cu in (5.8 L) Packard V8 and TwinUltramatic transmission were phased out and replaced by American Motors's new V8 and by GM Hydra-Matic and Borg-Warner transmissions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors combined the Nash and Hudson product lines under a common manufacturing strategy in 1955, with the production of Nashes and Hudsons consolidated at the Nash plant in Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Detroit Hudson plant was converted to military contract production and eventually sold.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The separate Nash and Hudson dealer networks were retained.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Hudsons were redesigned to harmonize with Nash's body styles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The fast-selling Nash Rambler model was sold as a Nash and a Hudson in 1955 and 1956.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] These badge-engineered Ramblers, and similarly the small Metropolitans, were identical except for the hubcaps, nameplates, and other minor trim.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The pre-existing full-size Nash product line was continued with the Nash Statesman restyled as the "new" Hudson Wasp and the Nash Ambassador restyled as the Hudson Hornet.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Although the cars shared the same body shell, they were at least as different from one another as Chevrolet and Pontiac.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Hudsons and Nashes each used their engines as they had previously: the Hudson Hornet continued to offer the 308 cu in (5.0 L) I6 that had powered the (NASCAR) champion during the early 1950s; the Wasp now used the former engine of the Hudson Jet.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Nash Ambassador and Statesman continued with overhead- valve and L-head sixes, respectively.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Hudson and Nash cars had different front suspensions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Trunk lids were interchangeable, but other body panels, rear window glass, dash panels, and braking systems differed.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Hudson Hornet, Wasp, and their Nash counterparts had improved ride, visibility, and fuel economy because of their lighter unitized Nash body.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The larger Nash and Hudson range did not sell well, and AMC lost money each year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Dismayed with the results, Romney decided in 1956 that the company's future lay with the compact Rambler line.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Romney halted production on the new large cars and focused entirely on the new Rambler Six and V8 introducing them in 1956, despite being scheduled for a 1957 release.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Sales of the new Ramblers were poor, and sales of the Hudson and Nash models were almost non-existent, resulting in a $31.7 million operating loss for 1956.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Sales improved in 1957, but the company saw a $11.8 million loss.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In response, Romney launched a massive public relations campaign, traveling 70,000 miles (112,654 kilometres) nationwide in 12 months.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Romney spoke at union halls, dinners, churches, fairgrounds, and radio and TV stations.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] He was anywhere where he could get the word out about Rambler.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Rambler sales took off in 1958, up 58.7%, and 425 new dealers were signed up.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] As a result, 1958 became AMC's first year of profitability since its formation, with $28 million in earnings.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Nash and Hudson brands were dropped, and Rambler became a marque in its own right and the mainstay of the company.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The popular British-built Metropolitan subcompact continued as a standalone brand until it was discontinued in 1961.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The prototype 1958 Nash Ambassador/Hudson Hornet, built on a stretched Rambler platform, was renamed at the last minute as "Ambassador by Rambler".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] To round out the model line, American Motors reintroduced the previous 1955, 100 in (2,540 mm) wheelbase Nash Rambler as the new Rambler American with only a few modifications.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This gave Rambler a compact lineup that included the reintroduced American, the 108 in (2,743 mm) wheelbase Rambler Six and Rebel V8, as well as the 117 in (2,972 mm) wheelbase Ambassador.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Sales of Ramblers soared in the late 1950s partly because of American Motors' focus on the compact car and its marketing efforts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] These included sponsoring the hugely popular Walt Disney anthology television series and as an exhibitor at the Disneyland theme park in Anaheim, California.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] George Romney himself pitched the Rambler product in television commercials.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] While the "Big Three" introduced ever-larger cars, American Motors followed a "dinosaur-fighter" strategy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Romney's leadership focused the company on the compact car, a fuel-efficient vehicle 20 years before there was a real need for them.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This gave Romney a high profile in the media.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Two core strategic factors came into play: (1) the use of shared components in American Motors products and (2) a refusal to participate in the Big Three's restyling race.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This cost-control policy helped Rambler develop a reputation for building solid economy cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Company officials were confident in the changing market and in 1959 announced a $10 million (US$110,445,205 today) expansion of its Kenosha complex (to increase annual straight-time capacity from 300,000 to 440,000 cars).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors was also beginning to experiment with non-gasoline-powered automobiles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] On April 1, 1959, American Motors and Sonotone Corporation announced a joint research effort to consider producing an electric car that was to be powered by a "self-charging" battery.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Sonotone had the technology for making sintered plate nickel–cadmium batteries that can be recharged very rapidly and are lighter than a typical automobile lead–acid battery.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In 1959, American Motors hired designer Dick Teague, who had previously worked for General Motors, Packard, and Chrysler; after Edmund E.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Anderson left the company in 1961, Teague was named principal designer and in 1964, vice president.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] To stay competitive, American Motors produced a wide range of products during the 1960s and added innovations long before the "Big Three" introduced them.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] For example, the Rambler Classic was equipped with a standard tandem master cylinder in 1962 that provided stopping ability even if there was a failure in the brake system.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Only Cadillac also included this safety feature six years before U.S. safety regulations required it on all cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] S. automotive industry, American Motors offered adjustable front seat backrests from their Nash-origin, and in 1964, the Classic and Ambassador were equipped with standard dual reclining front seats nearly a decade before the Big Three offered them as options.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Bendix disc brakes were made standard on the Marlin and optional on other models in 1965.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This made the Marlin one of the first modern American cars with standard disc brakes, while the Big Three did not offer them until the early 1970s on most of their models to meet Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In the early part of the decade, sales were strong, thanks in no small part to the company's history of building small cars, which came into vogue in 1961.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In both 1960 and 1961, Ramblers ranked in third place among U.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] S. automobile sales, up from third on the strength of small-car sales, even in the face of a lot of new competition.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Romney's strategic focus was very successful, as reflected in the firm's healthy profits year after year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The company became completely debt-free.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The financial success allowed the company to reach an agreement on August 26, 1961, with the United Auto Workers for a profit sharing plan that was new in the automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Its new three-year labor contract included generous annual improvement pay increases, and automatic cost-of-living raises.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] However, in 1962, Romney resigned to run for Governor of Michigan.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] His replacement was Roy Abernethy, American Motors' successful sales executive.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] By 1964, Studebaker production in the United States had ended, and its Canadian operations ceased in 1966.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The "Big Three", plus the smaller American Motors, Kaiser Jeep, International Harvester, Avanti, and Checker companies were the remaining North American auto manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Abernethy believed that American Motors's reputation of building reliable, economical cars could translate into a new strategy that could follow AMC buyers as they traded into larger, more expensive vehicles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors, in reality, had produced large cars throughout its history.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Rambler Ambassadors were as large as a full-sized Ford or Chevy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] There was only an absence of largest-sized cars from the American Motors lineup in 1963 and 1964 The first cars bearing his signature were the 1965 models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The 1965 models were a major makeover of the new platform that had just been introduced in 1963.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] These were a longer Ambassador series and new convertibles for the larger models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] During mid-year, a fastback, called the Marlin, was added.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] It competed directly with cars like the Dodge Charger, but AMC's "family-sized" fastback emphasized personal-luxury.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The continuing quest "in the business world's toughest race – the grinding contest against the Big Three automobile makers" also meant annual styling changes requiring large expenditures.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors's management total confidence "that the new 1965 models would stem a bothersome decline" actually began falling behind in share of sales.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Moreover, a new line of redesigned cars in the full and mid-sized markets was launched in the fall of 1966.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The cars won acclaim for their fluid styling, and Abernethy's ideas did work as Ambassador sales increased significantly.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] However, the dated designs of the Rambler Americans hurt its sales, which offset gains from Ambassador sales.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] There were quality control problems with introducing the new full-sized cars and persistent rumors of the company's demise because of its precarious cash flow.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Consumer Reports' negative ratings for American Motors' safety did not help.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] During this time, AMC's international sales were expanding.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] From only 18,000 cars five years ago, the 1965 model year AMC sold 74,420 vehicles in Canada, Europe, and Latin America.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] AMC remained the most significant U.S. seller of autos in both France and Germany.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Abernethy also called for the de-emphasis of the Rambler brand because he believed the public associated it too strongly with economy cars and that it was hindering the sale of American Motors' other models at a time when mid and luxury car sales were robust.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] As a result, he ordered that for 1966, the Ambassador and Marlin were to be badged purely as a product of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The strategy shift at first seemed to be working because sales of the redesigned 1965 and 1966 Ambassadors improved, even as AMC's overall production decreased from the record level achieved in 1963.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] However, corporate earnings per share were a meager 27 cents per share, the lowest since AMC made its famous compact car comeback in 1958.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Investors received a message of the changing fortune of the automaker when the company's 1966 annual financial report was delivered in a plain brown wrapper, instead of the previous year's glossy cover.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] A completely new design was also slated for the larger 1967 models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This strategy added $60 million in retooling costs, a significant stretch for the company.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The latest models shared fewer parts and were more expensive to build.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Abernethy continued his objective to position the new Rebel and Ambassador designs on an equal basis with competitive economy models marketed by the Big Three.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors did not have their own electric car program as did the Big Three, and after some negotiation, a contract was drawn in 1967 with Gulton Industries to develop a new battery based on lithium and a speed controller designed by Victor Wouk.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] A nickel-cadmium battery powered 1969 Rambler station wagon demonstrated the power systems that according to the scientist was a "wonderful car".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This was also the start of other "plug-in"-type experimental American Motors vehicles developed with Gulton – the Amitron city concept car and later the similar Electron.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Although the new models were well received by the motor industry media, the last quarter sales for AMC ended September 30, 1966 (AMC was not on a calendar fiscal year) were disappointing.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The company recorded a balance sheet loss of $12,648,000 for the year before Tax Credits and deferred Tax Assets.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] By this time the board had lost confidence in Abernethy due to his vast spending which had unstabilized the company and each year under his leadership the company had suffered substantial financial losses.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] As a result, Abernethy was forced into taking an "early retirement" from American Motors on January 9, 1967.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Chapin quickly instituted changes to American Motors's offerings and tried to regain market share by focusing on younger demographic markets.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Chapin's first decision was to cut the price of the Rambler to within $200 of the basic Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Innovative marketing ideas included making air conditioning standard on all 1968 Ambassador models (available as a delete option).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This made American Motors the first U.S. automaker to make air conditioning standard equipment on a line of cars, preceding even luxury makes such as Lincoln, Imperial, and Cadillac.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The company introduced exciting entries for the decade's muscle car boom, most notably the AMX.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] At the same time, the Javelin served as the company's entrant into the sporty pony car market created by the Plymouth Barracuda and the Ford Mustang.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Additional operating cash was derived in 1968 through the sale of Kelvinator Appliance, once one of the firm's core operating units.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Kelvinator divestiture left American Motors a downsized company solely manufacturing automobiles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Rambler marque was discontinued for the larger 1968 domestic models, leaving only the small Rambler American as the last product to bear the name through 1969.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Rambler brand continued to be used only for export markets, with Mexico being the last market to use it in 1983.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] From 1970, American Motors was the brand used for all American Motors passenger cars, and all vehicles from that date bore the American Motors name and the new corporate logo.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] However, "American Motors" and "AMC" were used interchangeably in corporate literature well into the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The branding issue was further complicated when the company's Eagle all-wheel drive passenger cars were marketed as the American Eagle in the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In the late 1960s, Kaiser Industries Corporation decided to leave the automotive industry and sought a buyer for its money-losing Kaiser Jeep division.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors' vice president for manufacturing, Gerald C.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Meyers, headed the team sent to evaluate Kaiser's Jeep factories.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Although opposed by AMC's top management, Chapin made a significant decision in February 1970 to purchase Kaiser Jeep for $70 million.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Although it was a gamble, Chapin believed Jeep vehicles would complement American Motors' passenger car business.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] (The latter being the only Nissan-branded vehicle in the United States until the 1980s when the Datsun name was phased out in favor of Nissan.) Jeep by far had the largest market share of the 4x4 market during this time.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors gained the iconic Jeep brand of light trucks and SUVs, as well as Kaiser-Jeep's government contracts – notably the M151 line of military Jeeps and the DJ-Series postal Jeeps.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors also expanded its international network.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The military and special products business was reconstituted as "American Motors General Products Division", later reorganized as AM General.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In 1970, American Motors consolidated all passenger cars under one distinct brand identity and debuted the Hornet range of compact cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Hornet and the later Gremlin shared platforms.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Gremlin, the first North American-built subcompact, sold more than 670,000 units from 1970 through 1978.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Hornet became American Motors' best-selling passenger car since the Rambler Classic, with more than 860,000 units sold when production ended in 1977.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Hornet platform continued to be built under various models through 1987.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] For a time, both the Hornet and Gremlin could be ordered with Levi's denim interiors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors supplied Mark VII Limited owner Jack Webb with two Matadors, a sedan and a wagon, for use in his popular television series *Adam-12*, increasing the cars' public profile.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Matadors saw fleet use as taxis, government, police, and fire vehicles in some states.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In 1973, American Motors signed a licensing agreement with Curtiss-Wright to build Wankel engines for cars and Jeeps.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Starting in 1974, the Matador sedan and station wagon were mildly refreshed, with new boxier front and rear ends, making it full-sized.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This second-generation model was produced virtually unchanged until 1978.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Sagging sales and tight finances resulted in the discontinuation of the Matador line after the 1978 model leaving American Motors to focus almost exclusively on its Hornet platform-based cars and the Jeep line.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] From 1970, the Rebel and Ambassador were identical from the A-pillar back.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Ambassador continued as AMC's upmarket model with higher trim, more equipment, and air conditioning as standard.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] From the A-pillar forward, the Ambassador was redesigned and stretched 7 inches (178 mm) to become the biggest ever, just as the 1973 Arab Oil Embargo sparked gasoline rationing across the nation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The additional length was due to a new front-end design and more substantial energy-absorbing bumpers required of all automobiles sold in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Sales of all large cars fell due to economic problems and rising gasoline prices.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Ambassador became a full-sized car in 1974 and was discontinued after the 1974 model year, leaving only the Matador as American Motors' full-size offering.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Nash and American Motors made Ambassadors from 1927 through 1974, the longest use of the same model name for any American Motors product and, at the time, the longest continuously used nameplate in the industry.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In 1974, the first-generation Matador two-door hardtop, known as the "flying brick" due to its poor aerodynamics in NASCAR competition, was replaced with a sleek, smoothly shaped, and radically styled two-door coupe.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The model received praise for its design, including "Best Styled Car of 1974" by *Car and Driver* magazine, customer satisfaction, and sold almost 100,000 coupes over five years.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Matador Coupe shared few components with the Matador sedan and station wagon other than suspension, drive train, some trim, and interior parts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In 1974, American Motors's AM General subsidiary began building urban transit buses in cooperation with Flyer Industries of Winnipeg, Manitoba.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] A total of 5,431 *Metropolitan* buses, including 219 electric trolley buses, were built before production ceased in 1979.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Production of diesel buses had ceased in 1978, with only trolley bus production taking place in 1979.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The AMC Pacer, an innovative all-new model introduced in March 1975 and marketed as "the first wide small car", was a subcompact designed to provide the comfort of a full-sized car.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Its pre-production development coincided with tightened U.S. federal passenger emissions and auto safety regulations.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Pacer sold well its first two years with 262,772 combined units sold in the US.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] With the Arab Oil Embargo of 1973, General Motors aborted the Wankel rotary engine around which the Pacer had been designed, as its fuel consumption exceeded that of conventional engines with similar power.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Therefore, American Motors's existing 258 and 232 cu in (4.2 and 3.8 L) AMC Straight-6 engines were used in the Pacer instead.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The fuel economy was better than the expected rotary engine's, but the I6's gas mileage was relatively low in light of the new focus on energy efficiency.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Also, as the Pacer shared few components other than the drivetrain with other American Motors cars, it was expensive to make, and the cost increased when sales fell steeply after the first two years.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Pacer line was discontinued in mid-1980.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] However, "AMC used cars, as far back as 1967, had the advantage of good warranty coverage ... so most owners were conscious of low-cost car maintenance ...
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] AMC units became some of the very best buys on the used car market" by 1975.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The 1977 Gremlin had redesigned headlights, grille, rear hatch, and fascia.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] For economy in the fuel crisis, American Motors offered the car with a more fuel-efficient Volkswagen-designed Audi 4-cylinder engine 2.0 L (122 cu in).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The engine was expensive for American Motors to build, and the Gremlin retained the less costly but less economical 232 cu in (3.8 L) as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] It was a sporty appearance package on the Hornet hatchback featuring upgrades, as well as the 258 cu in (4.2 L) inline six as standard with a choice of three-speed automatic or four-speed manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was optional with the automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] As all Matadors now received standard equipment that was formerly optional (e.g., power steering, automatic transmission), the "Brougham" package was dropped from 1977.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Optional on the Matador coupe was a landau vinyl roof with opera windows, and top-line Barcelonas offered new two-tone paint.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] For the 1978 model year, the Hornet platform was redesigned with an adaptation of the new Gremlin front-end design and renamed AMC Concord.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors targeted it at the emerging "premium compact" market segment, paying particular attention to ride and handling, standard equipment, trim, and interior luxury.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Gremlins borrowed the Concord instrument panel, a Hornet AMX-inspired GT sports appearance package, and a new striping treatment for X models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The AMC Pacer hood was modified to clear a V8 engine, and a Sports package replaced the former X package.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] With falling sales of Matador Coupes, sedans, and wagons, their 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was dropped, leaving only the 258 cu in (4.2 L) Inline-6 (standard on coupes and sedans) and the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 (optional on coupes and sedans, standard on wagons).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The two-tone Barcelona luxury package was offered on Matador sedans, and two-tone red paint was introduced as an additional Barcelona option.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Matador production ceased at the end of the model year with total sales of 10,576 units.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Matador was no longer attractive as automakers struggled to overcome economic woes, including continuing fuel price increases and double-digit U.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] For the 1979 model year, the Spirit sedan replaced the Gremlin.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] A new fastback version of the car, the Spirit Liftback, proved successful.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In December, Pacer production ceased after a small run of 1980 models was built to use up parts stock.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Concords received a new front-end treatment, and in their final season, hatchbacks became available in DL trim.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Concord and Spirit models were dropped after 1983.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] However, Time noted record Jeep sales and a backlog of orders for AM General's buses.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In July 1977, it was announced that the General Services Administration of the Federal U.S. government had awarded AMC a three-year contract worth $15 million to lease 5,838 cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Since the beginning of the fiscal year on October 1, 1976, the GSA had purchased 8,700 cars from AMC for $30 million.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] On October 21, 1977, Roy Chapin Jr. retired, and Gerald C.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] On March 31, 1978, American Motors and Renault announced a sweeping agreement for jointly manufacturing and distributing cars and trucks that would benefit both.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] A month later, American Motors announced that it would halt the production of standard urban transit buses after about 4,300 were sold by its AM General subsidiary over a period of three years.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Environmental Protection Agency ordered the recall of all American Motors's 1976 cars (except those conforming to California emissions regulations) – some 270,000 vehicles— plus 40,000 1975 and 1976 Jeeps and mini trucks, for correction of a fault in the pollution control system.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Total cost was estimated at up to $3 million, or more than AMC had earned the previous quarter.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors lost an estimated $65 million on its conventional (non-Jeep) cars for the fiscal year that ended September 30, 1978, but strong Jeep sales helped the company to an overall $36.7 million profit on sales of $2.6 billion.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] However, American Motors faced costly engineering work to bring their Jeeps into compliance with a federal directive for all 4-wheel-drive vehicles to average 15 mpg‑US (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) by 1981.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In December 1978 the government of Iran, embroiled in the Iranian revolution, cut off oil exports to the world.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This caused a devastating effect on all American automobile makers and American consumers.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Gasoline prices jumped 52 percent between September and December 1979.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Each of the Big Three (Ford, General Motors, Chrysler) lost money throughout 1979 leading to Chrysler becoming insolvent and considering bankruptcy by September.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Ford survived only because of its European operations, eventually losing $7 billion in domestic sales from 1979 to 1982.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] During the crisis, and with its domestic market share at 1.83%, American Motors struck a deal with Renault, the nationally owned French automaker in October 1979.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] AMC would receive a $150 million cash injection, $50 million in credits, and also the rights to start building the Renault 5 in 1982 (a deal for Renault products to be sold through the American Motors-Jeep dealer network had already been made in 1979).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In return, Renault acquired a 22.5% interest in American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This was not the first time the two companies had worked together.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Lacking a prestige model line in the early 1960s, Renault assembled CKD kits and marketed Rambler cars in France.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] A drop in Jeep sales caused by the declining economy and soaring energy prices began to constrict American Motors' cash flow.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] At the same time, pressure increased on the company's non-Jeep product lines.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The face-lifts and rebranding of American Motors' once-innovative and successful cars were not enough in a competitive landscape that had changed dramatically.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] No longer was the threat limited to the Big Three automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In response to the 1979 oil crisis, the Big Three had resorted to importing foreign motor vehicles, mainly Japanese models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Japanese models were mass-marketed and had lower manufacturing costs.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] By the end of 1980 Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Indeed, the share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Japanese manufacturers (Honda, Toyota, and Nissan) used streamlined production methods such as outsourcing and Just In Time (JIT) supply-chain management.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] They had new, highly efficient assembly plants in the United States.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] And now they targeted the heart of American Motors' passenger product line: small cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In early 1980, the banks refused American Motors further credit.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Lacking both capital and resources for the new, truly modern products it needed to offer, the company turned to Renault for a $90 million loan (US$351,676,090 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] By September that year, American Motors's U.S. market share had fallen to 1.7%, and in November sales dropped 19.1%.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors warned stockholders that the company could be bankrupted if they did not approve a plan for Renault to acquire as much as 59% of the company.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] On December 16, 1980, American Motors shareholders "overwhelmingly approved making the French Government-owned Renault" their company's principal owner.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Jean-Marc Lepeu, former corporate treasurer at Renault, became vice president for finance at American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In September 1981, Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault veteran of 23 years, mainly in manufacturing, became American Motors' executive vice president for manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In January 1982, the company's president W.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Meyers as chairman and CEO, and Dedeurwaerder moved up to be president.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] By this time Renault owned 46% of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Dedeurwaerder brought a broad perspective at this critical time: he is credited with streamlining many of American Motors' arcane management techniques.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] He also instituted important improvements in plant layouts, as well as in cost and quality control.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Having increased its stake in the company several times to keep it solvent, Renault eventually owned 49% in 1983.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Some view this development as ending American Motors' run as a truly American car company.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] New ownership and management heralded a new product venture for American Motors: a line of modern front-wheel drive cars, designed by Renault, to be produced at Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In 1980, all American Motors cars received a new rust-proofing process using Ziebart as Factory Rust Protection.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The extra protection also included aluminized trim screws, plastic inner fender liners, and galvanized steel in every exterior body panel, along with the unibody getting a deep-dip (up to the window line) bath in epoxy-based primer.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In August 1979, for the 1980 model year, American Motors introduced four-wheel-drive versions of the Spirit and Concord, calling the collective line the AMC Eagle.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Eagles rapidly became one of the company's best-known products and are considered one of the first "crossover SUVs".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Eagles used the 2-wheel drive body shells mounted on an all-new platform developed by American Motors in the late 1970s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Featuring an innovative full-time four-wheel-drive system, it sold best in snow-prone areas.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Sales started strongly but declined over time.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] While the two-wheel drive Spirit and Concord were discontinued after 1983 as the company concentrated on its new Renault Alliance, the Eagle survived for five years longer, albeit only in station wagon form, into the 1988 model year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This meant the four-wheel-drive Eagle was the lone representative of the American Motors brand from 1984 until the 1988 model year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] All the company's remaining output was branded Renault or Jeep.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The last AMC Eagle was built on December 14, 1987.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Renault Alliance was the first joint product of the American Motors-Renault partnership.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Introduced in 1983, the Alliance was a front-wheel-drive Renault 9 compact car slightly restyled for the American market by Dick Teague, mainly to comply with American safety standards, and produced by American Motors at Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The car was badged as a Renault, and some cars also carried American Motors badges.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] It was available as a sedan with two or four doors and later as a convertible.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The hatchback, introduced in 1984 and badged as the Renault Encore, was the same as the European Renault 11 model.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The new model, introduced during increased interest in small cars, won several awards, including Motor Trend Car of the Year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] *Motor Trend* declared: "The Alliance may well be the best-assembled first-year car we've ever seen.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Way to go Renault!" The Alliance was listed as number one on *Car and Driver's* list of ten best cars for 1983.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The positive reception and sales of 200,000 Alliances by 1984 was hindered by the availability of only two body styles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Alliance was a European-designed car that was not fully suited to U.S. market demands.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The distribution network was also not well supported, which led to the lower quality delivered by dealerships with "disastrous consequences" for the image of the automobiles and high warranty costs because of quality failings, which greatly impacted sales from 1985 to the end of production in 1987.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] After the 1983 model year, American Motors focused entirely on four-wheel drive autos; the company stopped producing rear-wheel-drive cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors facilities were then used to assemble the Renault-branded Alliance and Encore compact and subcompact cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] For the final 1987 model year, a higher-performance version of the Alliance 2-door sedan and the convertible was sold as the Renault GTA.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] This version had a Renault two-liter engine that was exclusive to it and not shared with the European Renault 9 and 11 models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Encore models were renamed Alliance Hatchback in 1987.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Alliance and GTA production ended in June of that year, while the Renault 9 and 11 models continued through the 1988 model year in Europe, being replaced by the all-new Renault 19.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] More beneficial to American Motors' future was the introduction of an all-new line of compact Jeep Cherokee and Wagoneer models in the autumn of 1983 for the 1984 model year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Renault's François Castaing, head of AMC's product development team, designed the new Jeep platform with styling by Dick Teague.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Renault was interested in selling the Cherokee in Europe, but the vehicle needed to be lighter and more fuel-efficient to meet European expectations.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The new XJ weighed 3,100 pounds (1,406 kilograms), due to its unibody construction and lighter components such as the front seats taken from the Renault 9 and 11 and new Renault Alliance.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] AMC's initial forecasts of 40,000 Cherokee and Wagoneer sales were shattered, with sales amounting to 75,000 in their first year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The three leading off-roading magazines, *Petersen's 4-Wheel & Off-Road*, *Four Wheeler*, and *Off-Road* each named the new Jeep Cherokee as the "4x4 of the year." The popularity of these downsized Jeeps pioneered a new market segment for what later became defined as the sport utility vehicle (SUV).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] They initially used the AMC 150.4 cu in (2.5 L) OHV four-cylinder engine with a carburetor, and a General Motors-built 2.8 L (171 cu in) carbureted V6 was optional.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] In 1986, throttle-body injection replaced the carburetor on the 2.5 L I4 engines.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] A Renault 2.1 L (128 cu in) Turbo-Diesel I4 diesel was also offered.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Starting with the 1987 models, a new 4.0 L (244 cu in) I6 engine, derived from the older 258 cu in (4.23 L) I6 with a new head design and an electronic fuel injection system, replaced the outsourced V6.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] American Motors' "new" engine was designed with help from Renault and incorporated Renault-Bendix (Renix) parts for fuel and ignition management.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The 4.0 developed an outstanding reputation for reliability and toughness.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Retained by Chrysler after the buyout, the design received continuous improvements and refinements until its discontinuation at the end of the 2006 model year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The AMC 4.0 engine saw extensive application in XJ Cherokees and Wagoneers, Grand Cherokees, and Wranglers, and many of those engines saw (or are seeing) extremely long lives, quite a few exceeding 300,000 mi (480,000 km).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Chrysler built the XJ Cherokee until the end of the 2001 model year in the U.S. and until 2005 in China.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Unlike most sport-utility vehicles based on adapted pickup truck designs, the Cherokee XJ SUV came first, and the Comanche was designed as a later pickup truck version.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] Production of the full-sized pickups ceased after 1987.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p01] The Grand Wagoneer and 360 V8 engine were dropped after 1991 (the last American-made vehicle whose engine used a carburetor for fuel delivery), and the Comanche was discontinued after 1992.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Significant changes occurred in 1985 as the market moved away from American Motors' small models.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] With fuel relatively cheap again, buyers turned to larger, more powerful automobiles, and American Motors was unprepared for this development.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Even the venerable Jeep CJ-5 was dropped after a *60 Minutes* TV news magazine staged exposé of rollover tendencies under extreme conditions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors also confronted an angry workforce.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Labor was taking revenge, and reports circulated about the sabotage of vehicles on the assembly lines because of the failure to receive promised wage increases.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] There were rumors that the aging Kenosha plant was to be shut down.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] At the same time, Chrysler was having trouble meeting the demand for its M-body rear-drive models (Dodge Diplomat, Plymouth Gran Fury, and Chrysler Fifth Avenue).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Because they were assembled using the old "gate and buck system" and the tooling could be easily moved, Chrysler could supply the components and control the quality while AMC assembled the car.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Cappy agreed to use some of AMC's idle plant capacity in Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In January 1985, Renault's chairman in France, Bernard Hanon, was dismissed by the government in a shake-up triggered by huge losses as a result of his goal to revolutionize Renault's product strategy in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] He was instrumental in 1981 for the company to invest in AMC and also made Renault a full-line automaker, but this ballooned the firm's debt.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Renault relinquished its number one sales position in Europe, which it held from 1980 until 1983.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The company had been losing money since 1981 and had fallen to sixth place behind Ford, Fiat, Volkswagen, Peugeot, and General Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Strikes plagued Renault at the end of 1984, and the French government introduced price controls that severely cut the profit margins on cars sold in France, Renault's most important market.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Hanon was replaced by Georges Besse, ex-president of Produits Chimiques Ugine Kuhlmann in France.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Paul Tippett resigned to become president of a textile company.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Dedeurwaerder, president since 1982 and chief executive officer since September 1984, announced at the Paris Auto Show in October 1985, that AMC would begin imports of the innovative seven-seat, front-wheel-drive Espace minivan in the spring of 1986.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] This was part of expanding the range of Renault models that include plans for marketing the Renault Alpine GTA/A510 sports car through select AMC dealers.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In December 1985, Dedeurwaerder became chairman of AMC's executive committee while continuing as the company's president and CEO.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Joe Cappy was moved up from executive vice president to chief operating officer, and Tippet's position was filled by an ex-Renault vice president, Pierre Semerena.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Semerena made his managerial reputation as a no-nonsense cost cutter.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The new management responded with tactical moves by selling the lawn care Wheel Horse Products Division and signing an agreement to build Jeeps in the People's Republic of China.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The Pentagon had problems with AM General, a significant defense contractor, being managed by a partially French-government-owned firm.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The U.S. government would not allow a foreign government to own a substantial portion of an important defense supplier.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] As a result, the profitable AM General Division was sold to LTV Corporation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Another milestone within AMC's management was the departure of Dick Teague.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] He was American Motors' design vice president for 23 years - an industry record. he was responsible for many Jeep and AMC designs, including the Javelin, AMX, Hornet, Gremlin, Pacer, Matador coupe, and the Cherokee XJ.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In France, Renault continued to experience financial trouble.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The investment in American Motors (including the construction of a new Canadian assembly plant in Brampton, Ontario) forced cuts at home, resulting in the closure of several French plants and mass layoffs.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In addition, Jeep vehicles were riding an unprecedented surge in demand.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] It seemed to Besse and others that American Motors was on course for profitability.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] However, on November 17, 1986, Besse, who had a high-profile among French capitalists, was assassinated by a member of a French clandestine far-left extremist group, Action Directe.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] AMC's plans to reinvigorate sales with higher-priced Renaults continued for a little longer, with the plan being a three-pronged lineup beginning with the mid-sized Medallion, the larger Premier above it, and the sporty Renault Alpine providing a halo car.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The Medallion and the Premier both went on sale, but Alpine never made its planned mid-1987 rollout.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Under pressure from Renault executives following Besse's death, Renault's new president, Raymond Levy, set out to repair employee relations and divest the company of its investment in American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Renault owned 46.1% of American Motors' outstanding shares of stock.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In 1986, American Motors posted a $91.3 million loss.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The earlier agreement between Chrysler and American Motors in 1985, under which American Motors would produce M-body chassis rear-drive large cars for five years from mid-1986 through 1990, fed the rumor that Chrysler was about to buy AMC.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] According to the head of manufacturing for Chrysler, Stephan Sharf, the existing relationship with AMC producing a car for a competitor facilitated the negotiations.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] On March 9, 1987, Chrysler agreed to buy Renault's share in American Motors, plus all the remaining shares, for about $1.5 billion ($4,250,878,735 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chrysler made no secret that they were only interested in AMC for Jeep, AMC's new assembly plant in Canada, and AMC's network of 1,300 dealerships nationwide.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] With the sale complete, American Motors became the Jeep-Eagle division of Chrysler on August 25, 1988, and was fully merged as of March 29, 1990.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The sale came at a time when the automotive press was enthusiastic about the proposed 1988 lineup of Renault, Eagle, and Jeep vehicles and reported that the small automaker's financial outlook was improving.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors' quarterly results for all of 1987 were positive.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chrysler purchased American Motors when the company appeared to be in an excellent financial position with its new product line.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] It was the Jeep brand that Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca wanted – in particular, the ZJ Gen. of the Grand Cherokee, then under development by Jeep engineers, which ultimately proved highly profitable for Chrysler (the nameplate remains in production today).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] However, the buyout included other attractive deal sweeteners for Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Among them was the world-class, brand-new manufacturing plant in Bramalea, Ontario, which offered Iacocca an unprecedented opportunity to increase his company's production capacity at a fire-sale price.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors had designed and built the plant in anticipation of building the Renault 25-based Eagle Premier.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Renault left the U.S. market entirely as a brand in 1987.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Thus, the Renault Medallion was sold through the new Jeep-Eagle division as an Eagle, not a Renault.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The Jeep-Eagle division was formed from the American Motors Jeep Renault dealer network.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The Jeep and Eagle vehicles were marketed primarily by former American Motors dealers.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The American Motors badge was last used on the Eagle Sports Wagon through the 1988 model year, then eliminated, and the Eagle car brand was phased out by 1998.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The 1954 merger of Nash-Kelvinator Corporation and Hudson Motor Car Company that established American Motors was led by Nash-Kelvinator president George W.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Mason to reap benefits from the strengths of the two firms to battle the much larger "Big Three" automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The merger was initially intended to be three-way, with Packard being the number three.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Mason had first discussed the possibility of a merger with Packard president James J.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Nance insisted that if Packard were to join, he would have to be the CEO of the new company.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Mason fully intended to lead the new company, thus the deal did not go through.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Packard acquired Studebaker two months after Nash acquired Hudson.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Mason became CEO and president of the new company, and Hudson's president A.E.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Barit retired to become an American Motors board member.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Mason selected long-time Nash associate and future governor of Michigan, George W.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Roy Abernethy, ex-vice president of sales for Willys, was hired to be vice president of sales.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Following Mason's sudden death on October 8, 1954, Romney took over, reorganizing the company and focusing American Motors' future on a new small car line.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Mason's death also allowed Romney to put an end to any further discussions for a merger between American Motors and Studebaker-Packard.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] By the end of 1957, the legacy Nash and Hudson brands were completely phased out and replaced with the Rambler and Metropolitan brands.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The company struggled initially, but Rambler's sales took off under Romney.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] A Rambler won the 1959 Mobil Economy Run, and by 1960, was the third-most-popular brand of automobile in the United States, behind Ford and Chevrolet.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] George Romney left American Motors in 1962 to run for governor in Michigan and was replaced as CEO by Roy Abernethy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Abernethy had been with AMC since the 1954 merger and as vice president of sales was responsible for successfully building AMC's sales and distribution network during the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] After two model years (1963 and 1964) of only producing compact cars, Abernethy shifted the focus of American Motors back to bigger and more profitable cars such as the Ambassador line and tried to move away from the perceived negative of the Rambler's economy car image.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] However, the enormous costs of developing the new cars and engines meant American Motors now had problems in securing working capital to keep the company going.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors sales dropped 20% in the first half of 1966, and the firm reported a fiscal six-month loss of $4.2 million on sales of $479 million.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Evans invested more than $2 million because American Motors's stock was selling for only 60% of the company's net worth; thus, he became its largest stockholder and was named its chairman on June 6, 1966, replacing Richard E.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Cross, who continued as a director and chairman of the executive committee.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In the quarter ending September 30, 1966, American Motors recorded a loss of $12,648,000 before tax credits and deferred tax assets.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In the face of deteriorating financial and market positions, Abernethy "retired" as CEO in 1967, and Evans "resigned" as chairman.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chapin Jr., the son of Hudson co-founder Roy D.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors' public explanation for the removals was that the two had "stepped aside according to a plan to give a younger team an opportunity to move the company forward".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chapin took charge of revitalizing the company, and designer Dick Teague economized by developing several vehicles from common stampings.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The AMC Matador was in reality a facelift of the AMC Rebel, itself derived from the 1967 AMC Ambassador platform.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] While prices and costs were cut, Teague designed new and more sporty automobiles resulting in the Javelin and AMX muscle cars; and the AMC Hornet.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] From 1970 Jeep production complemented AMC's existing passenger-car business.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Under Chapin's leadership, AMC produced all-new compact car designs based on the Hornet platform including the Gremlin and Concord.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Meyers replaced the retiring William Luneburg as president and Chief Operating Officer.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Only 5 months later, upon the retirement of Chapin, Meyers became chairman and CEO on October 21, 1977.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] At the time, Meyers was 49 years old, and became the youngest top executive in the automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Meyers abandoned AMC's policy of head-on competition and instead focused on revamping its four-wheel drive vehicles, a market segment left untended by the large automakers, and by acquiring advanced technology.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Meyer's began talks with Renault in 1979 and from 1980, American Motors partnered with the French automaker to help finance their manufacturing operations, obtain much-needed capital, and source subcompact vehicles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] On December 16, 1980, Renault became the principal owner of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] At age 53, Meyers retired from the company in February 1982.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] By that time, Renault controlled 46% of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Meyers was succeeded as chairman by former American Motors president W.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] At the time, Tippett was a member of American Motors management for only three years but had overseen almost all vehicle-making operations during his time as president.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault manager, replaced Tippet as president.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Tippet's tenure as CEO was short-lived and in September 1984, he was replaced by Dedeurwaerder.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] On September 28, 1984, Dedeurwaerder was promoted to CEO, with Tippett remaining on as chairman.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] On February 25, 1985, AMC announced its first full-year profit since 1979.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The success was short-lived as on July 31, 1985, AMC announced that it had received a $50 million loan from Renault following a second-quarter loss of $70.4 million.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Under Dedeurwaerder, Chrysler entered an agreement with American Motors in 1985 to produce Dodge Diplomats and Plymouth Furys, as well as Dodge Omnis and Plymouth Horizons in American Motors' Kenosha, Wisconsin, plant.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] At the time, American Motors had excess manufacturing capacity.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In January 1986, Dedeurwaerder was named Renault's executive vice president of worldwide sales and marketing.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] He remained president and CEO, and chairman of the executive committee at AMC until March 23, 1986, when he was succeeded in the former two roles by Joseph E.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] By 1986, Renault had lost $700 million on $22 billion of sales in the U.S. market, and was $9 billion in debt.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] On March 23, 1986, former executive vice president of operations Joseph E.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Cappy was named president and chief executive officer of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chrysler acquired American Motors in August 1987.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The primary task of Chrysler management was to integrate the two companies as quickly as possible.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors' final CEO, was tasked with achieving this by Chrysler president Gerald Greenwald.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] After the buyout Cappy joined Chrysler as group vice president of the new Jeep-Eagle division.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In 1989, he was named Chrysler's vice president of brand development.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The following year he became Chrysler's vice president of international operations.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors was forced to constantly innovate for 33 years until Chrysler absorbed it in 1987.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The lessons learned from this experience were integrated into the company that bought American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The organization, strategies, and several key executives allowed Chrysler to gain an edge over the competition.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Even today, the lessons gained from the American Motors experience continue to benefit other firms in the industry.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] There are many legacies of American Motors's business strategies.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors could formulate strategies that industry critics often evaluated as "strokes of brilliance".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chapin Jr., American Motors realized they were up against the giants of the industry, so to compete successfully they had to be able to move quickly and with ingenuity.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] An essential strategy practiced by American Motors was to rely on outside vendors to supply components in which they had differential advantages.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] This approach was finally accepted within the U.S. auto industry, but only after each of the Big Three experienced the failure of attempting to be self-sufficient.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Another example of American Motors' agility was the ability of management to squeeze money out of reluctant bankers, even in the face of bankruptcy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] These core abilities helped save the company from collapse and, after each obstacle, gave it the wherewithal to keep it operating.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Ironically, American Motors was never stronger than just before its demise.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors' managers anticipated important trends in the automotive industry.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] It preached fuel efficiency in the 1950s, long before most auto buyers demanded it.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Led by American Motors' Rambler and several European cars, the small car innovation reduced the Big Three's market share from 93% in 1957 to 82% in 1959.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The company inherited foreign manufacturing and sales partnerships from Nash and continued developing business relations, decades before most of the international consolidations among automobile makers took place.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors was the first U.S. automaker to establish an ownership agreement with a foreign automaker, Renault.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Although small in size, American Motors was able to introduce numerous industry innovations.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Starting in 1957, American Motors was the only U.S. manufacturer to fully immerse all automobile bodies in primer paint for protection against rust, until competitors adopted the practice in 1964.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Even one of American Motors's most expensive new product investments (the Pacer) established many features that were later adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] These included aerodynamic body design, space-efficient interiors, aircraft-style doors, and a large greenhouse for visibility.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors was also effective in other areas, such as marketing, by introducing low-rate financing.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors' four-wheel-drive vehicles established the foundation for the modern SUV market segments, and "classic" Jeep models remain the benchmark in this field.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chapin drew on his experiences as a hunter and fisherman and marketed the Jeep brand successfully to people with like interests.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The brand developed a cult appeal that continues.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The purchase of American Motors was instrumental in reviving Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] According to Robert Lutz, former president of Chrysler, the American Motors acquisition was a big and risky undertaking.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The purchase was part of Chrysler's strategic "retreat-cum-diversification" plan that he states did not have the proper focus.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Initially, the goal was to obtain the world-renowned Jeep brand.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] However, Lutz discovered that the decision to buy American Motors turned out to be a gold mine for Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] At that time, Chrysler's management was attempting to find a model to improve structure and operations, *"something that would help get our minds unstuck and thinking beyond the old paradigms that we were so familiar with*".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In this transformation, *"Chrysler's acquisition of AMC was one of the all-time great moments in corporate serendipity*" according to Lutz *" that most definitely played a key role in demonstrating how to accomplish change*".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] According to Lutz (1993), while American Motors had its share of problems, it was far from being a bunch of "brain-dead losers".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] He describes the "troops" at American Motors as more like the Wake Island Marines in battle, "with almost no resources, and fighting a vastly superior enemy, they were able to roll out an impressive succession of new products".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] After first reacting with anger to the purchase, Chrysler managers soon anticipated the benefits.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] To further solidify the organizational competencies held by American Motors, Lee Iacocca agreed to retain former American Motors units, such as engineering, completely intact.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In addition, American Motors' lead engineer, François Castaing, was made head of all engineering at Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In an unthinkable strategic move, Castaing completely dismantled the entrenched Chrysler groups.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In their place, American Motors's "platform team" was implemented.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] These were close-knit cross-functional groups responsible for the whole vehicle, contrasted with Chrysler's highly functional structure.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In this capacity, Castaing's strategy was to eliminate the corporate administrative overhead bureaucracy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] This move shifted corporate culture and agitated veteran executives who believed that Chrysler's reputation as "the engineering company" was being destroyed.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Yet, according to the popular press, by the 1980s, Chrysler's reputation was shot, and in Lutz's view, only dramatic action would change that.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In summary, Chrysler's purchase of American Motors laid the critical foundation to help re-establish a strategy for its revival in the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Top managers at Chrysler after the AMC buyout appeared to have made errors similar to those by American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] For example, Chrysler invested heavily in new untested models while not keeping up its profitable high-volume lines.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The American Motors influence also continued at General Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] GM recruited a new executive team to turn itself from near bankruptcy in the early 2000s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Among the new strategists at GM was Lutz, who understood the importance of passion in product design.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Lutz's new thinking at GM incorporated the systems and structures that originated from American Motors's lean and focused operations.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Renault implemented the lessons it learned from its investment in American Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The French firm took a parallel approach as it did with its initial ownership of American Motors and applied it to resurrect the money-losing Nissan automaker in Japan.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In 2009, in a deal brokered by the Obama administration, Italian automaker Fiat initiated a white knight takeover of Chrysler to save the struggling automaker from liquidation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The two firms would later fully merge to create Fiat Chrysler Automobiles in 2014, and would further merge with the French firm PSA Group, owners of the Citroën and Peugeot brands, to form Stellantis in 2021.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chrysler revived the "Spirit" name, which was discontinued by AMC after 1983 for use on one of its A platform cars (the Dodge Spirit) from 1989 until 1995.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The planned Renault Medallion was sold as the Eagle Medallion in 1988 and 1989.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The full-sized Premier's platform was far more advanced than anything Chrysler was building.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Plymouth almost received their rendition of the LH platform, which was to be called the Accolade.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Still, Chrysler decided to drop this version just before LH production started.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The Chrysler 300M was likewise a Premier/LH-derived car and was initially to have been the next-generation Eagle Vision until the Eagle brand was dropped after 1998.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The LH Platform was subsequently re-engineered, using Mercedes-Benz components, into the Chrysler LX Platform, which was the basis for the Chrysler 300, Dodge Charger, and Dodge Challenger.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chrysler's successor Stellantis later revived the Hornet name in 2023 for Dodge as a rebadged variant of the Alfa Romeo Tonale.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chrysler marketed the SJ Jeep Grand Wagoneer until 1991, leaving it almost entirely unaltered from the final American Motors rendition before the buyout.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The Jeep Comanche pickup truck remained until 1992, while the Cherokee remained until 2001 in the United States.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The XJ Cherokee was produced in China through 2006 as the Cherokee 2500 (2.5L) and Cherokee 4000 (4.0L).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Although it was not introduced until 1993, the Jeep Grand Cherokee was initially an American Motors-developed vehicle.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Traces of American Motors remained within.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors' Toledo, Ohio, plants continued to manufacture the Jeep Wrangler and Liberty, as well as parts and components for Chrysler, Dodge, and Jeep vehicles (although Toledo Machining and Forge were closed in 2005).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Although heavily downsized, American Motors' main plant in Wisconsin operated as the Kenosha Engine Plant, producing engines for several Chrysler Group products, including the Wrangler.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The plant was closed as part of the post-bailout restructuring of Chrysler in October 2010.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The 4.0 L (242 cu in) engine was used until the 2006 model year by DaimlerChrysler in the Jeep Wrangler.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] American Motors' technologically advanced Bramalea Assembly and Stamping Plants in Brampton, Ontario, later produced the LX-cars – the Chrysler 300, Dodge Challenger, Dodge Charger, and the now discontinued Dodge Magnum.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Both were retired when the Wrangler was completely redesigned for the 2007 model year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] AM General, sold by American Motors in 1983, is still in business building the American Motors-designed Humvee for American and allied militaries.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] AM General also built the now-discontinued civilian variant, the H1, and manufactured a Chevrolet Tahoe-derived companion, the H2, under contract to GM, who acquired the rights to the civilian Hummer brand in 1999.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] GM was forced to phase out the Hummer brand in early 2010 due to its bankruptcy restructuring after offering it for sale, but failing to find a suitable buyer.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Although Chrysler introduced new logos for its brands in the 1990s and again in 2010 after the Fiat Group took control of the company, Jeep still uses the American Motors-era logo introduced shortly after American Motors purchased the brand in 1970.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Until the Chrysler purchase, Jeep's logo also featured the American Motors emblem.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Beginning in 1960, American Motors' executive vice president of international operations Roy D.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chapin Jr. embarked on a strong international campaign to set up importation and local assembly operations of American Motors vehicles worldwide.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] In five years, Chapin increased foreign sales to 73,489 cars, which at the same time grew AMC's share of the U.S. export market from 2.5 percent to 14.3 percent.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] Chapin successfully established or re-established vehicle assembly operations in Argentina, Australia, Belgium (via Renault of France), Chile, Costa Rica, Germany, Iran, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Philippines, South Africa, and Venezuela.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] He also strengthened international export operations with exports to the United Kingdom, Denmark, Finland, Iceland, and Norway in Europe, and to countries in the Middle East, the Caribbean, and South America.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] The Rambler Classic would become the basis of Argentina's future national car, the Torino.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] After becoming CEO in 1967, Chapin organized the acquisition of Kaiser Jeep from Kaiser Industries in 1970, with American Motors, thereby inheriting all existing international Jeep operations.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] These helped sustain American Motors during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p02] While the Rambler marque had been dropped in the United States after the 1969 model year, all export markets retained the Rambler name, with the longest to retain it being Mexico until 1983.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The initial building was built during 1926–27 by the Electric Refrigeration Corporation (subsequently Nash-Kelvinator) with design by Amedeo Leoni, industrial layout by Wallace McKenzie, and tower enclosure and industrial units by William E.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] War Department contracted with Nash-Kelvinator to produce 900 Sikorsky R-6 model helicopters.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] As part of that contract, a 4.5 acres (1.8 ha) site north of the factory was used as the smallest airport in the world as a flight testing base.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Nash-Kelvinator produced about 50 R-6s a month during the war.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] When the contract was terminated at the war's end, 262 helicopters had been constructed.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] During Chrysler's occupancy of the complex, it was known as Jeep and (Dodge) Truck Engineering (JTE), including facilities for body-on-frame work as well as testing facilities and labs.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The buildings included 1,500,000 square feet (140,000 m2), approximately one-third devoted to engineering and computer functions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] As of 2007, Chrysler employed over 1,600 people at the complex, moving those operations in mid-2009 to the Chrysler Technology Center.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The property was put up for sale by Chrysler in early 2010.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] It was bought by a local man who gutted the building for scrap and left it in a dilapidated state before losing it to foreclosure.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The abandoned building was in possession of the city of Detroit and officials were considering if the industrial site would be more marketable if the building was torn down.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] In 2018, the Wayne County Commission approved a land swap that included a new jail complex for the county as well as a potential revival for the old American Motors building.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The era of 1900 until 1925 saw various corporations, in several U.S. states, use similar "American" names, such as American Motor Carriage Company (Ohio, 1902–1903), American Automobile Manufacturing Company (Indiana, 1911–1912), and American Motors Incorporated (New York, 1919–1920).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] In 1916, an earlier "American Motors Corporation", apparently unrelated to the more famous later corporation of the same name, was formed in Newark, New Jersey, with Louis Chevrolet as vice president and chief engineer.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] By 1918, it was producing cars in a plant at Plainfield, New Jersey.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] In 1923, it merged with the Bessemer Motor Truck Company of Pennsylvania into Bessemer–American Motors Corporation, which lasted less than a year before merging with the Winther and Northway companies into Amalgamated Motors.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] A new company was formed in Palmdale, California, in 2001.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Registration for the American Motors trademarks was filed in 2001 by this California-based firm.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The company's website specifically claimed no affiliation to the previous American Motors but used American Motors' history and logos on its website.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The website is now dead, and the company's claims to American Motors' trademarks expired in 2005.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The new Chrysler LLC holds a live registration for the name "American Motors", which was applied for in 2005.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The "AMC" wordmark, complete with "A-mark" graphic logo, as was originally used in 1970 and through the late-1980s, was registered and published for comment by Chrysler as of 2010.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Also: Kaiser Jeeps used the AMC 327, Buick 225 ("Dauntless V6"), Buick 350 ("Dauntless V8"), and Willys 134 I4 ("Hurricane").
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The downsized Jeep XJ Cherokee/Wagoneer used the Chevrolet 2.8 L V6 in 1983–1984.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] American Motors contracted with Volkswagen to buy tooling for the Audi 2.0 L OHC I4.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Major parts (block, crankshaft, head assembly) were initially purchased from Audi and shipped to the U.S., where American Motors accomplished final assembly at a plant explicitly purchased for the production of this engine.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Sales never reached numbers to justify taking over total production.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] American Motors made several changes to the engine.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] By contractual agreement, they were prevented from using the Volkswagen or Audi names in association with the American Motors assembled version.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] American Motors models historically regarded by hobbyists as particularly "collectible" include the Javelin, AMX, and performance specials such as the 1957 Rambler Rebel, 1965–67 Marlin, 1969 Hurst SC/Rambler, 1970 Rebel Machine, and 1971 Hornet SC/360.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] These models enjoyed limited popularity when new, resulting in low production figures.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] In January 2007, the AMC AMX was "really taking off in the muscle car market" according to the editors of *Hemmings Classic Car*, and it had "left its mark among AMC collectors' minds as a great alternative" to higher-priced Hemi-powered muscle cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The early Javelin (1968–70) stands out from the Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler pony cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Mays, automotive historian and author of *The Savvy Guide to Buying Collector Cars at Auction*, the "Wow!
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Factor" is an important and measurable pleasure to an owner whether their car is driven or sits in a climate-controlled garage.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Moreover, the author's collector car, a 1969 Ambassador station wagon, made friends as strangers came to greet and host him as if "long lost kin".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Mays points out the ready availability of parts for American Motors engines and his experiences in having service done on Ramblers without being charged for the work in exchange for the experience of driving a "sassy Rambler" (a 1966 American convertible) and having pictures taken with it.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Other American Motors models, once somewhat ignored by the hobby, are now considered "future collectibles".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] Examples include the 1959 Ambassador 4-door hardtop station wagon, of which only 578 were produced, and the Jeep Scrambler CJ8, a combined pickup truck-Jeep, of which only a few thousand were made.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The AMC Gremlin is described as having "a cult-like following" in today's collectible car market.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The Gremlin shares components with some other American Motors models, making its repair and restoration relatively inexpensive compared with other "historic cars".
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The AMC Pacer increased in value according to a Pacer owner who is the CEO of a major insurance provider for collector car owners.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] There are active Rambler and American Motors car clubs in the U.S. and elsewhere (examples in External Links).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] In April 2008, *Hot Rod* magazine released an article claiming that American Motors was in the process of being revived.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] The vehicles in the works were to be the AMX, Matador, Ambassador, Pacer, and Gremlin.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] It was a popular article, illustrated with drawings of the concept cars entering production and accompanied by plentiful information.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/american-motors-p03] However, it was later revealed as an April Fools' joke.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Known as the "City of Murals", Belvidere is home to several public art installations throughout the North and South State Street historic districts, which are on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] These historic districts are home to the Boone County Museum of History, the Funderburg House Museum, several restaurants and bars, and antique and boutique stores.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Popular festivities like Heritage Days are held yearly.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Before the arrival of the mostly Anglo-Americans in the 19th century, this area was long occupied by the Illinois Confederation, a loose grouping of up to 12 to 15 Native American tribes.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The main tribes were the Cahokia, Kaskaskia, Michigamea, Peoria, and Tamaroa.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] After trading, warfare and other encounters with French traders, who entered this area before the Anglo-Americans, their numbers declined.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] In large part due to the high mortality from new infectious diseases, which adversely affected Native Americans across the continent.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The area developed as Belvidere was first settled by European Americans in 1835: Simon P.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] They named this location next to the Kishwaukee River as "Elysian Fields" from Greek mythology.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Because new residents could not pronounce or spell the proposed name, the city was eventually renamed after Belvidere, Virginia, the former home of Ebenezer Polk, a railroad lawyer and major financial founder in the city.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Belvidere originally developed on the north side of the Kishwaukee River.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] In 1851 the Galena and Chicago Union Railroad was built south of the river, stimulating the relocation of much of the business section to the south side of the river, giving access to railway transportation.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Belvidere's downtown is now on the south side.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Major industries developed along the river and railroad, including the National Sewing Machine Company, which operated here from 1886 to the 1940s.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] In 1906, former female sheriff Sarah Ames moved to South Dakota; she named the area where she settled after her home town.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Belvidere, South Dakota still operates as a small town in Jackson County.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] On April 21, 1967, a devastating tornado struck Belvidere.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Twenty-four people died as a result, many of them schoolchildren.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The F4 tornado struck at the end of the school day of Belvidere High School, when many children, including those who attended area grade schools, were waiting outside the high school for school buses.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Of the sixteen school buses outside the high school, twelve were overturned or thrown by the tornado.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The tornado did $22 million in damage, demolished over 100 homes, and injured 500 people.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] In 2007 a statue was erected in front of Belvidere High School in memorial of the lives lost.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] As of 2013, the Belvidere tornado was the sixth worst weather disaster to happen at an American school, and the deadliest since 1955.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] On December 7, 2009, an explosion occurred at an NDK America building, when a large pressure vessel ruptured during a crystal-growing process.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Pieces of debris, some weighing several tons, were flung over a wide area.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] One piece struck an automotive supply building and injured an employee inside.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Chesterfield, Indiana native Ronald Greenfield, a truck driver refueling at the nearby Belvidere Oasis truck stop, was struck and killed by a 7-foot support beam.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The shockwave was felt over a wide area.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] No NDK employees were injured in the incident.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The Chemical Safety Board investigated the incident, issuing their final report in 2013.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The CSB found that stress corrosion cracking had occurred, unnoticed, in one of the crystal-growing autoclaves, leading to the catastrophic failure.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] They also found that NDK management had been warned multiple times over the years that the dangerous levels of hot sodium hydroxide inside the vessels would corrode the steel walls.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] However, NDK management insisted buildup of byproducts from the crystal-growing process would passivate the vessel walls against the corrosion.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] However, the vessel that ruptured had never been internally inspected to test the passivation theory, during its many years of service.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] After a smaller leak occurred in January 2007, NDK was warned about safety concerns again, this time by insurance investigators, who were ultimately ignored.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Finally, the CSB determined the method for growing crystals used at NDK's Belvidere facility was prohibitively dangerous in the first place, pointing out such methods had been already abandoned by other crystal-growing facilities in favor of safer, lower-pressure and lower temperature processes.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Following their own 2010 investigation, the Occupational Safety and Health Administration fined NDK more than half a million dollars for willful disregard for legal requirements, and "unacceptable" indifference to safety and health.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The NDK facility was demolished in 2015, with no plans to rebuild.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] On March 31, 2023, an EF1 tornado struck Belvidere.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] It caused the Apollo Theatre to collapse during a concert for the Floridian Death Metal band Morbid Angel and Brazilian Death Metal band Crypta.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The concert proceeded despite advanced notice of severe conditions expected that day.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The collapse led to over 40 injuries; leaving at least four in critical condition and one fatality.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] According to the 2021 census gazetteer files, Belvidere has a total area of 12.30 square miles (31.86 km2), of which 12.06 square miles (31.24 km2) (or 98.08%) is land and 0.24 square miles (0.62 km2) (or 1.92%) is water.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Located in north central Illinois, in a county on the northern border of the state, Belvidere is approximately 75 miles (121 km) northwest of the downtown of Chicago, and approximately 12 miles (19 km) east of Rockford.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Belvidere developed on both sides of the Kishwaukee River in north central Illinois.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] It is 76 miles from downtown Chicago via Routes 20, 76 and the Northern Illinois Toll road.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] Belvidere is an industrial community surrounded by prosperous farms.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] It is the county seat, with an estimated 2006 county population of over 52,000.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] The altitude is 800 feet above sea level, with average temperatures of: 73 degrees F in the summer; 24 degrees F in the winter, and the average rainfall is 33.3 inches, and the average annual snowfall is 35.3 inches.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] As of the 2020 census, Belvidere had a population of 25,339.
[src:chrysler-fifth-avenue/belvidere-illinois] 25.7% of residents were under the age of 18 and 14.5% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
